<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, Sept. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Missile' Fired at Britain's MI6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Unknown attackers fired a ''small missile'' at the
headquarters of Britain's MI6 intelligence agency in central London late
Wednesday, causing an explosion on the eighth floor, police said. The blast
caused limited damage and no injuries at the 10-story structure at the heart of
Britain's intelligence abroad. Witnesses reported hearing two explosions, large
enough to send up a plume of white smoke and to rattle buildings across a
railway. The blast brought firefighters, police and ambulances to the site on
the south bank of the River Thames, and police closed the area around the
headquarters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
38 Iraqis Detained on Mexican Border
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Agents held 38 Iraqis at the Mexican border Wednesday after
small groups of them tried to walk into the United States without visas, INS
officials said. Mexican police detained about 150 others in a Tijuana hotel
room. A letter from someone claiming to represent the group said the Iraqis are
Chaldeans, who are Christian, who were tired of waiting in Tijuana for
permission to enter the United States and decided to present themselves en masse
at the border, according to an INS official speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban Plane Survivors En Route to U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- The remaining eight Cuban survivors of a plane crash
in the Gulf of Mexico were being transferred to a Coast Guard cutter to be
brought to Key West for medical evaluation today, a U.S. Coast Guard spokesman
said. A ninth survivor was already being treated in Key West for head and neck
injuries. ''The Coast Guard has decided to go ahead and medically evacuate the
remaining eight Cuban migrants,'' Petty Officer Scott Carr said. U.S. law lets
Cubans apply for residency if they reach U.S. soil.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge: Government Not Liable for Waco Deaths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- A federal judge cleared the government of any wrongdoing
in the deaths of 80 Branch Davidians during the 1993 standoff with federal
agents at the cult's compound. U.S. District Judge Walter Smith's ruling, issued
late today, mirrors the conclusions an advisory jury and Special Counsel John
Danforth reached in July. Both have said Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
agents and others were not responsible for the deaths on the final day of a
51-day standoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Twelve Colombia Hostages Freed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Amid clashes with troops, leftist rebels on
Wednesday released twelve of the hostages they seized last weekend along a
highway in Colombia. Two soldiers died in the fighting in western mountains
above Cali, Colombia's third largest city. The military claimed the attack
forced the guerrillas to free the hostages. Officials the leftist National
Liberation Army, or ELN, still holds 43 hostages. An estimated 80 people were
kidnapped Sunday, most from roadside restaurants along the Via Al Mar.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
EU Ministers Criticize France
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- European Union transport ministers criticized France on
Wednesday for giving a tax break to truckers protesting high fuel prices, a move
that inspired similar anti-tax blockades across Europe. While EU ministers held
an emergency meeting and failed to coordinate their tax policies amid the
protests, thousands of fishermen and farmers shut down ports in Spain,
surrounded wholesale fish markets and blockaded fuel distribution centers for a
sixth day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Rejects Spending Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate rebelled against its Republican leaders
Wednesday and rejected a bill that would give lawmakers an election-year raise
while providing nearly $33 billion for the Treasury and other agencies. The
69-28 vote set back GOP plans to begin quickly resolving lingering budget fights
with President Clinton.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Thursday following the previous day's
sharp advance. The Nikkei Stock Average fell 67.37 points to 16,390.94 points in
early trading. On Wednesday the average closed up 334.12 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Send Ewing To Sonics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Patrick Ewing's 15-year career with the Knicks ended
Wednesday as New York sent him to the Seattle SuperSonics in a four-team,
12-player trade also involving the Los Angeles Lakers and Phoenix Suns. The
Knicks sent Ewing to Seattle and received Glen Rice from the Lakers and Luc
Longley from the Suns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinals Beat Astros, 11-6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Cardinals became the first team to clinch a
playoff spot this season, winning the NL Central on Wednesday night when Jim
Edmonds' grand slam sent them to an 11-6 win over the Houston Astros. A sellout
crowd at Busch Stadium saw the Cardinals win the division title for the first
time since 1996, manager Tony La Russa's first year with the team.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
