<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal investigators probing jail visits to Torricelli donor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Federal officials are investigating if allies of
New Jersey Sen. Robert Torricelli pressured a Democratic
fund-raiser not to cooperate with authorities, The New York Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Articles in other papers have said the FBI and federal
prosecutors with the Campaign Financing Task Force are examining
whether the donor, David Chang, received preferential treatment
during a three-day stay at the Hudson County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   One paper, The Jersey Journal of Jersey City, has said
investigators have asked whether Chang received sexual favors from
a female jail guard.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, 57, of Cresskill, admitted in June that he broke election
laws by funneling $53,700 into Torricelli's successful 1996 Senate
campaign. As part of a plea bargain he agreed to assist the task
force.
</P>
<P>
   While at the jail in Kearny for a weekend in December after his
arrest by FBI agents, Chang says he was visited by several men he
had not seen before, the Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chang told prosecutors that one of the men told him not to
cooperate with authorities, while another simply put a finger to
his lips, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about report, Chang lawyer Bradley D. Simon said
Wednesday, ''I can't discuss it because of the pending
investigation, and he's a cooperating witness.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Simon denied that Chang had sex in jail: ''That is
complete fiction. It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli spokesman Eric Shuffler said Wednesday, ''This is the
latest in a series of meritless allegations. One seems more bizarre
than the next. There is absolutely no truth to the suggestion that
anyone associated with this office tried to intimidate or
discourage David Chang from cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   Myron Marlin, a task force spokesman at the Justice Department,
said Wednesday he could not comment on the report. Officials cannot
generally comment on pending investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of the investigation have also been reported in The
Record of Hackensack and The Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The jail investigation started in late July, the Times said.
Since then, FBI agents have seized log books and videotapes, said a
Hudson County spokeswoman, Julie St. Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Three guards - Lt. Kelvin Roberts, Enrique Marrero and James
Nieves - who were at the jail that weekend appeared before a
federal grand jury on Aug. 24, said their lawyer, Daniel J. Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think these allegations are ridiculous,'' Welsh told The
Associated Press. ''Nothing untoward happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh said he did not know what Chang's specific allegations
were, due to grand jury secrecy rules, but called the sex
suggestions ''pretty much of a farce.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Budnick, a senior prison official who supervises the
three guards, also is expected to be questioned. The Times said
Budnick went to the jail that weekend at the request of an aide of
Hudson County Executive Robert C. Janiszewski.
</P>
<P>
   Budnick has said he ordered that Chang get another blanket after
getting a phone call from William W. Northgrave, the county
counsel, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
   Budnick lawyer Peter R. Willis has said his client did nothing
wrong. He was at a trial Wednesday and unavailable for comment, his
office said.
</P>
<P>
   Janiszewski denied intervening on Chang's behalf and said
Budnick ''simply would not be doing anything improper.''
</P>
<P>
   Northgrave told the newspaper he could not comment on whether he
called Budnick until the inquiry is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is among 25 people charged by the task force and among
seven who have admitted wrongdoing in connection with Torricelli
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli raised $9.2 million to defeat Rep. Richard A. Zimmer
in 1996. His fund-raising ability led to his appointment as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
