<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports talk host sued for saying Miss America pageant fixed  </HEADLINE>
By BILL BERGSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - The Miss America Pageant sued radio talk
show host Howard Eskin for slander Wednesday for saying the contest
was fixed. Eskin said he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty pageant filed suit in U.S. District Court in Camden,
N.J., against Eskin and Infinity Broadcasting Corp., owner of
Philadelphia radio station WIP-AM, said Robert M. Renneisen Jr.,
chief executive officer of the pageant.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that Eskin's remarks might raise doubts that
could hurt the pageant's ability to raise scholarship money,
Renneisen told a news conference at the Philadelphia office of the
pageant's attorneys. It does not specify an exact amount of damages
being sought.
</P>
<P>
   Eskin said his comments were facetious and the radio station
said the lawsuit was without merit.
</P>
<P>
   Renneisen and attorney Steven P. Perske played a tape of an Aug.
22 broadcast in which Eskin chatted about revealing the winners of
contests such as CBS television's ''Survivor'' series. He went on
to say, ''I hope people know Miss America's fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Before they get into the weekend, they know who's going to
win,'' Eskin said on the tape. ''They already know, you know,
through all the screenings and all the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   A co-host mentioned ''all the judges out there,'' and Eskin
replied: ''That's phony.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eskin said in a statement issued by the station: ''I made
the comment in jest, and certainly did not think any of our
listeners would take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Eskin made a tongue-in-cheek comment in the context of a
humorous discussion about revealing the winners of contests ahead
of the public announcement,'' WIP general manager Butch Foster
said. ''WIP believes any lawsuit would be without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Renneisen said the Atlantic City, N.J.-based pageant received
phone calls about Eskin's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We started hearing, 'Did you know this guy is saying these
things on the air, is it true?''' Renneisen said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the lawsuit was not just another attempt to boost
interest in the 79-year-old pageant after sagging television
ratings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's certain types of publicity you seek and there's
certain types you don't,'' he said. ''Yes, we have fun with it. Are
we going to have two-piece or one-piece swimsuits? Who's going to
be the judge, who's going to be the host? ... Those are all things
that ... are part of the normal hype.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What's happened here is Mr. Eskin and Infinity Broadcasting
have accused us of a crime, of fraud,'' Renneisen said. ''That's a
lie. Not only is it a lie but it's a lie put in a malicious context
so that's slander.''
</P>
<P>
   The pageant had not yet measured any potential impact on its
scholarship-raising abilities but would do so as part of preparing
its case for court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.missamerica.org
</P>
</TEXT>
