<DOCNO> APW20000921.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Lending Practices Slacken  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Risky loans banks made to U.S. businesses have
more than doubled in two years -- to $100 billion -- prompting
worries that banks are loosening their credit standards too much as
they joust for market share, according to a federal report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared by the Office of the Comptroller of the
Currency, said consumer lending standards have also slackened in
such areas as home-equity loans, as the percentage of consumer debt
held in those is at a five year-high.
</P>
<P>
   ''We remain quite concerned about the high levels of ... credit
risk on the books of some banks as a result of relaxed underwriting
and risk selections in prior years,'' John D. Hawke Jr., the
comptroller of the currency, said in a statement accompanying the
report.
</P>
<P>
   He said the OCC is also ''apprehensive'' about an increase in
highly leveraged lending, ''and the frequency with which these
activities are being undertaken without adequate analysis and risk
management systems at some banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators worry that the combinations of these forces
could find banks unprepared for losses if the economy droops. That
could mean businesses would be unable to renegotiate their loan
terms and consumers would be more exposed to bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The $100 billion in troubled business loans represents 5.1
percent of commercial loans surveyed -- ones of $20 million or more
made by three or more banks. The loans totaled $45 billion, or 2.5
percent, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that:
</P>
<P>
   --More banks loosened commercial loan standards in 2000, 16
percent versus the 13 percent that loosened standards in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   --Many types of loans that make up a large chunk of credit risk
''have experienced little or no tightening during the past six
years.''
</P>
<P>
   --For the fifth straight year, the level of credit risk in bank
portfolios increased. ''This was true for almost every lending
product,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   --Competition and market strategy were the most frequent reasons
given for easing underwriting standards.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth annual survey of lending practices covered the 69
largest national banks, whose combined loans total $1.9 trillion,
89 percent of national bank loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0034 </TRAILER>
