<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Track and Swimming Headline for NBC  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- For the first time in these Olympics,
the two marquee sports of the games -- track and swimming -- will
make up the bulk of NBC's primetime television schedule Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Track competition begins Friday (Thursday EDT) and swimming ends
Saturday (Friday EDT) so the sports have just two days of
competition overlapping each other. That means NBC gets a full
plate of big names from both sports for Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   From the track, Marion Jones begins her quest for five gold
medals, running preliminary heats of the women's 100-meter dash,
and Maurice Greene, the world's fastest man after lowering the
100-meter record to 9.79 seconds, gets started in his showcase
race.
</P>
<P>
   There are four finals set for the Aquatic Center -- the women's
800 freestyle, where American Brooke Bennett is the defending gold
medalist, the men's 50 freestyle with Russian Alexander Popov
resuming his personal battle with American Gary Hall Jr., the
women's 200 backstroke and the men's 100 butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Also on NBC's Friday night primetime schedule are the men's shot
put and 20-kilometer walk from the track, women's platform diving
from the pool and the women's trampoline final in gymnastics. Late
night coverage includes the United States vs. Australia in women's
volleyball and the men's final in weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC has the United States vs. New Zealand in softball, rowing
semifinals, men's beach volleyball and the finals in women's super
heavyweight weightlifting. Boxing continues on CNBC, which also
will show the United States women vs. New Zealand in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Greene missed the 1996 Olympics at Atlanta and has made Sydney
his compulsion ever since. At Athens in 1999, he lowered Donovan
Bailey's world record for the 100 from 9.84 seconds to 9.79 and
then punctuated that time with a 9.80 at the world championships,
where he also won the 200 and anchored America's gold medal 400
relay team.
</P>
<P>
   He faces a strong field at the Olympics including training
partner Ato Bolden of Trinidad and Tobago. Bailey of Canada, the
defending champion in the 100, has made a remarkable recovery from
a ruptured Achilles tendon two years ago and teammate Bruny Surin
has matched his 9.84 time for the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is entered in five events at Sydney -- the 100, 200, long
jump, 400-meter relay and 1,600 relay. She is the world champion in
the 100, and saw her task become simpler when top rival Inger
Miller pulled out of the event because of a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   She pulled up with a back injury during the 100 at the world
championships and missed the rest of the 1999 season, but has come
back to be a heavy multi-medal favorite at the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In the pool, Bennett is strongly favored to defend the 800
freestyle gold medal she won in Atlanta when two-time gold medalist
Janet Evens finished sixth. Her time of 8:23.92 at the Olympic
trials was the fastest in the world at that distance since 1989.
Kaitlin Sandeno gives the United States another strong entrant in
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Popov and Hall are longtime rivals and have staged some riveting
races. Most memorable, perhaps, was the duel in the pool at Atlanta
where the Russian touched first, becoming the only man in history
to win the Olympic 50 freestyle twice. Complicating the rematch is
Pieta van den Hoogenband, the Flying Dutchman, who tied his own
world record winning the 200 freestyle and broke the world mark in
the 100 freestyle semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who has diabetes, had to cut back on his training for a
while after the long trip from the United States caused his blood
sugar levels to fluctuate. American Anthony Ervin could be a factor
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Nina Zhivanevskaya is favored in the 200 backstroke with
Japanese swimmers Tomoko Hagiwara and Miki Nakao expected to
challenge. Americans Amanda Adkins and Lindsay Benko are outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Michael Klim, already part of two relay wins, goes
for another gold in the men's 100 butterfly with Sweden's Lars
Frolander and Australian Geoff Huegill also expected to be factors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0038 </TRAILER>
