<DOCNO> APW20000921.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alternative Transportation in LA  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With buses and trains idled by a strike, the
area's working poor are finding their own solution: private cars
whose owners charge a few dollars for a ride along the same routes
abandoned by buses.
</P>
<P>
   The grass-roots shuttle network saved thousands of people from
walking to work or not getting there at all.
</P>
<P>
   Raquel Ortega, 30, found a ride in a private van after walking
2&AMP;frac12; hours Wednesday morning toward her job in a T-shirt factory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to work,'' said the single mother of four. ''If not,
we starve to death.''
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority and the union
representing striking bus drivers and rail operators spent 10 hours
in negotiations Wednesday and plan to resume talks on Friday. Both
sides said some agreement was reached on secondary issues but that
key economic points, including benefits and wages, remained.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're anxious to settle this,'' said MTA spokesman Marc
Littman, expressing disappointment that no negotiations would be
held Thursday because union officials plan to participate in a
support rally. ''We'll be back here at the table whenever they want
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldy Norton, spokesman for the United Transportation Union,
representing bus drivers and train operators said: ''The parties
did get some things accomplished. But we didn't get to the big
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the state Department of Industrial relations, a
member of Gov. Gray Davis' cabinet, was attending the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout, which began Saturday, has halted most public
transit in a 1,400-square-mile area and affected some 450,000
commuters, including many of the region's poorest residents.
</P>
<P>
   On average, bus and rail riders earn $15,000 a year, according
to MTA. Most don't own cars and have been forced to walk, ride
bicycles, hitchhike or arrange other rides.
</P>
<P>
   So, many are relying on the steady stream of cars and vans
pulling up to bus stops offering rides for $2 to $6 each way.
That's steep for a worker making California's minimum wage of $5.75
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The rides-for-hire trade is illegal -- charging a fare requires a
special license and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers caught doing it risk having their vehicles impounded and
face a $1,000 fine or a six-month jail term, said Robert Johnson,
senior investigator with the city Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We probably saw 100 to 150'' within an hour on Tuesday, he
said. ''You can go to just about any bus stop. It's so much that
... we can't curtail the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Police reported no arrests as of Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldo Pacheco, 41, began offering rides in his battered 1986
Dodge Ram van on Saturday. He said he makes about $40 a day --
spending half on gas -- for about four hours of driving that begins
at 6 a.m. Then he heads to a $250-a-week job as a driver picking up
sewing machine parts for a downtown business.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm worried for me because I need a little bit of money,''
said the father of three. ''I'm worried for the people because they
need transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   On his last trip Wednesday, Pacheco picked up five turbaned
Sikhs visiting from India. For $2 each, he took them to the beach
at Santa Monica, an hour-long drive that would have cost $25 to $30
in a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Singh, 23, joked about the inconvenience caused by the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is like India,'' he said. ''Nobody knows when the bus is
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press photographer Damian Dovarganes
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   MTA: http://www.mta.net
</P>
<P>
   United Transportation Union: http://www.utu.org
</P>
</TEXT>
