<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- In a day of injury and intrigue,
defending tennis gold medalist Lindsay Davenport left the Olympics
with a bad foot and track star Marie-Jose Perec departed Sydney
with some bad vibes.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the Atlanta champion and top seed at the Sydney
Games, defaulted her second-round match Thursday to end her hopes
of a second consecutive medal. She had aggravated her sprained left
foot in a first-round victory over Paola Suarez.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's surprising decision was announced just before she
was to take the court against Rossana De Los Rios of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, French track star Perec -- dubbed the ''Greta Garbo of
athletics'' -- decided she wants to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   The reclusive 1996 gold medalist fled Australia for Singapore
after she was threatened by a man who burst into her Sydney hotel
room, according to her main sponsor. There were no further details
provided on the mysterious incident.
</P>
<P>
   Her sudden departure led to ''will she or won't she?''
speculation Thursday (Wednesday night EDT) over Perec's Olympic
future, but her return seemed a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   ''She hasn't been officially excluded from the team,'' said
Michel Vial, head of the French delegation. ''At this point, being
in Singapore, it is very improbable that she will compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Kaigler, a spokeswoman for Reebok, said it was possible
that Perec could still compete in the Olympics. Earlier, she had
said Perec was definitely out.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed on one thing: Perec, 32, had left Sydney on a
plane bound for Singapore just one day before her scheduled heat in
the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Perec, who suffers from a rare disease that causes chronic
fatigue, had surprised French Olympic officials by disappearing
from her hotel room. Since arriving in Sydney, she had dodged the
media and refused to train with the French team; the Australian
media quickly compared her to the ultra-private Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   Perec was the defending champion in the 200 and 400 meters,
making her only the second women ever to complete that double.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- SOFTBALL: Tears of disappointment and disbelief were flowing
in the U.S. dugout after a third bitter loss in as many games for
the softball team. Lisa Fernandez surrendered a two-run homer as
Australia rallied in the bottom of the 13th inning to win 2-1 over
the numbed American, who had taken the lead in the top of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez lost despite striking out 25 and surrendering just two
hits. The defeat will, at minimum, cost the Americans (2-3) a bye
in the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- BOXING: Everything fell into place Thursday to set up the most
anticipated fight of the Sydney Games. U.S. 201-pounder Michael
Bennett, with a victory in his Olympic debut, advanced to a
quarterfinal showdown with Cuban heavyweight great Felix Savon.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 29, who started fighting after his July 1998 release
from prison, scored an 11-2 decision over Wojciech Bartnik of
Poland. Savon, trying to join fellow Cuban Teofilo Stevenson and
Lazlo Papp of Hungary as three-time boxing gold medalists, defeated
Rasmus Ojemaye of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   The first 10 American boxers in the ring have all won. Bennett
faces Savon next week.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- BAILEY'S ILLNESS: Atlanta gold medalist Donovan Bailey may
join Davenport on the sidelines. A viral infection had greatly
slowed the one-time world's fastest man.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's congested, he's not feeling well,'' Bailey's agent, Ray
Flynn, said Thursday morning (Wednesday night EDT). ''He's not
feeling 100 percent by any means. He's got flu-like symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition in the 100 meters begins Friday, and Bailey was
hopeful that he could be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in bed for two days,'' Bailey said.
''Psychologically, I'm very strong. But it's the physical thing I
have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- SWIMMING: The Americans continued to treat the Olympic pool
like a U.S. water park.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Bennett, the gold medalist in 1996, was top qualifier in
the preliminaries Thursday (Wednesday night EDT) in the 800-meter
freestyle. A victory in Friday's 800 final would put her with Janet
Evans (1988, 1992) as the only back-to-back winners in the grueling
event.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has already won Sydney gold in the 400 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hall Jr. of Phoenix qualified second in the preliminaries
of the 50 freestyle, just 14 hours after winning bronze in the 100
free. The field in the race was loaded, with two-time defending
champion Alexander Popov of Russia, Pieter van den Hoogenband of
the Netherlands and American Anthony Ervin.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifiers came after longshot Misty Hyman and relay team
anchor Jenny Thompson won gold medals in record times for the
American swimmers one night earlier.
</P>
<P>
   For Thompson, the 800-meter freestyle relay victory catapulted
her into rarified Olympic company. Her seven golds are more than
any woman swimmer, snapping a tie with Germany's Kristin Otto.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 27, who also has a silver in her career, tied Czech
Republic gymnast Vera Caslavaska for the second-most Olympic golds
by a woman. With teammates Samantha Arsenault, Diana Munz and
Lindsay Benko, she established an Olympic record of 7 minutes,
57.80 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Hyman shocked defending champion Susie O'Neill
of Australia to win the 200 butterfly. Hyman shocked herself, too;
upon seeing her Olympic-record time, she repeatedly said, ''Oh my
God! Oh my God!''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the red, white and blue celebration, the orange-clad fans
of the Netherlands had reason to cheer as a Dutchman nicknamed
''Hoogie'' turned some of the world's top swimmers into mere
blowfish.
</P>
<P>
   Pieter van den Hoogenband won gold in the 100 freestyle in 48.30
seconds, whipping two-time defending gold medalist Alexander Popov
of Russia. Popov settled for silver and American Gary Hall Jr. took
the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Van den Hoogenband became the first man to sweep the 100 and 200
freestyles since American Mark Spitz in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- TENNIS: The last women to defeat Venus Williams could await
the streaking U.S. tennis player in the Olympic quarterfinals.
Williams, whose 28-match win streak included titles at Wimbledon
and the U.S. Open, defeated Tamarine Tanasugarn of Thailand 6-2,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario of Spain won as well, defeating Patricia
Wartusch of Austria 6-2, 6-4. If both players win their next match,
they meet in the Olympic quarterfinals; Williams last loss was to
Sanchez-Vicario at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- BEACH VOLLEYBALL: With her dad, Olympic decathlon champion
Rafer Johnson, sitting amid the sellout crowd, American Jenny
Johnson Jordan and teammate Annett Davis reached the quarterfinals
with a 15-9 victory over Cuba. The Americans trailed 9-6 before
ripping off the last nine points of the match.
</P>
<P>
   America's other team, Holly McPeak and Misty May, advanced with
a tense 15-13 victory over Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   -- MEN'S VOLLEYBALL: With their third straight loss, the American
volleyball team was mired in last place and a longshot to take a
medal. Yugoslavia bashed the U.S. team (0-3) in straight sets,
25-15, 25-20, 25-23. While not mathematically eliminated, the
Americans will need help to reach the quarterfinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Withdraws From Olympics  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN WINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Defending champion Lindsay Davenport
withdrew Thursday from the Olympics because of a foot injury,
ending a bid by the U.S. team for a medals sweep in women's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Further tests were planned to determine whether the injury is a
stress fracture, and Davenport said she could be sidelined the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Her withdrawal means there will be no rematch in the final
against second-seeded Venus Williams, who beat Davenport this year
to win Wimbledon and U.S. Open titles.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, seeded No. 1, sprained the outside of her left foot
last month and aggravated the injury in a first-round win Wednesday
over Paola Suarez. Her withdrawal was announced just before she was
to take the court for a second-round match against Rossana De Los
Rios.
</P>
<P>
   ''To have to pull out of a tournament that's probably the
highlight of my career, it's devastating,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   She played through the injury at the U.S. Open and said she
wasn't concerned about it when she arrived in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was feeling OK until I started practicing on these courts,''
she said. ''They're stickier and harder on my foot than other
surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said the foot was sore following her first-round match
and worse when she tried to practice Thursday morning (Wednesday
EDT).
</P>
<P>
   ''It was hard to put any weight on it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won her 28th match in a row Thursday, beating Tamarine
Tanasugarn of Thailand 6-2, 6-3. Third-seeded Monica Seles beat
Miriam Oremans of the Netherlands 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. captain Billie Jean King had talked of Davenport being part
of a medals sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very sad moment she can't defend her gold medal
properly,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is a second-generation Olympian, and her victory in
Atlanta four years ago marked a career turning point. She has since
won three Grand Slam titles and earned the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since Atlanta ended I was looking forward to coming here,''
she said. ''I'm not angry. I'm just disappointed and sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' victory left her one round from a quarterfinal
showdown against the last player to beat her, Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario. The fifth-seeded Spaniard advanced to the third
round by beating Patricia Wartusch of Austria 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Williams lost to Sanchez-Vicario at the French Open, then began
her winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ''A few times she has gotten the best of me, but a few times
I've gotten the best of her,'' Williams said. ''So we'll see what
happens in that quarterfinal, given that we both get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her last loss, Williams has won Wimbledon and the U.S.
Open. Now she wants her first Olympic medal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd love that,'' she said with a grin. ''Everyone watches at
home, and you see people standing on the podium crying and shaking.
That would be a nice feeling. It's pretty rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Tanasugarn, Williams won playing less than her best. She
rarely ventured to the net and had 10 double faults, including
three in one game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I wasn't trying very hard,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams saved her only overhead for match point, slamming a
winner to close out the victory in 63 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In other second-round play, No. 8 Dominique Van Roost of Belgium
eliminated Russian Anastasia Myskina 6-2, 6-3, and No. 11 Nathalie
Dechy of France beat Australian Nicole Pratt 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   In men's action, second-seeded Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil beat
Rainer Schuttler of Germany 6-4, 6-4; third-seeded Swede Magnus
Norman defeated wildcard Paradorn Srichaphan of Thailand 7-5, 6-2;
fifth-seeded Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov beat Argentine Juan Ignacio
Chela 7-6 (4), 6-4; and No. 11 Mark Philippoussis of Australia
defeated wildcard Kristian Pless of Denmark 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven of the 16 seeded men survived the opening round. Jeff
Tarango is the only remaining American in men's singles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0148 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Isler Drops Down in 470 Fleet  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- J.J. Isler thought the women's 470
Olympic sailing competition was going to be wide open, and she was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Isler watched her overall lead disappear Thursday (Wednesday
night EDT) as she dropped into third place after four races. She
finished 15th out of 19 boats in the third fleet race, then
rebounded to finish third in the next race.
</P>
<P>
   Isler had finished sixth and first in the opening two races
Wednesday to hold a slight lead. She now trails skippers from
Germany and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Isler and several other skippers flew protest flags at the end
of the first race on the Pacific Ocean. Protests are heard at night
back at the Rushcutters Bay marina.
</P>
<P>
   Isler, of San Diego, and crew member Pease Glaser of Long Beach,
Calif., fell significantly behind while sailing downwind on the
second leg of the third race and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Foerster of Garland, Texas, finished fourth and 11th in the
men's 470 to move from eighth to sixth place overall after four
races. His crew member is Bob Merrick of Portsmouth, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   On the 49er course, brothers Jonathan and Charlie McKee, who
came into the day second overall, had their first poor day of the
series, finishing 14th and 13th. They did rebound to win the third
race of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers raced off the suburb of Manly, where the north wind
reached 12 knots at its highest, giving some kick to the winged
skiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The McKees' previous worst finish was sixth. They were the last
of the 17 crews to have a finish of 10th or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan McKee, 40, won the gold medal in the Flying Dutchman in
1984 and Charlie McKee, 38, won the bronze in the 470 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers will race 16 times while all other classes except
Soling race 11 times. The Soling fleet races concluded Wednesday,
with American skipper Jeff Madrigali finishing fourth to earn a
first-round bye in the match-racing series.
</P>
<P>
   Europe skipper Courtenay Becker Dey of The Dalles, Ore., the
1996 bronze medalist who was 21st after two races, finished fifth
in the third race. Race four went off late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Women's windsurfer Lanee Butler of Aliso Viejo, Calif., remained
fourth overall with a seventh-place in the seventh fleet race, and
Mike Gebhardt of Fort Pierce, Fla., was ninth overall after
finishing 10th.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Tornado crew of John Lovell of New Orleans and Charlie
Ogletree of Newport Beach, Calif., was second in the fifth fleet
race and remained in sixth place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Whitewater Saga Not Over  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, won't
be charged in the Whitewater investigation, but the country hasn't
heard the last of the saga that has its origins in a failed
Arkansas land deal in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Whitewater first came to public attention in the 1992
presidential campaign amid questions about the failure of a savings
and loan owned by the Clintons' Whitewater business partners, Jim
and Susan McDougal. On Wednesday, Independent Counsel Robert Ray
announced that there was ''insufficient'' evidence to prove beyond
a reasonable doubt that either one of the Clintons committed a
crime in Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's finding would seem to be the last word. But it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Here in question and answer form is a look at what's to become
of the most expensive criminal investigation in the two-decade
history of the independent counsel law, lasting throughout most of
Clinton's eight years as president.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If it's not over, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   A: A final report on the Clintons' conduct is being written by
prosecutors. Expected to run hundreds of pages, it will be filed
under seal with a federal appeals court, which will decide when to
release it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the report simply recite the facts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps, but if experience is any guide, it also could be
highly critical of the Clintons. Previous independent counsel
reports have stirred major controversy. One independent counsel's
final report suggested that a former U.S. attorney general, Edwin
Meese, probably broke the law, even though he never was charged. A
final report in the Iran-Contra arms and money affair suggested a
high-level criminal cover-up. Meese heatedly denied the
accusations, as did all the participants in the alleged Iran-Contra
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the report isn't even written yet, what's its
significance?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will be yet another battleground for the Clintons and
their political opponents in the years to come. If first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton is elected to the Senate, the report could
become a troublesome issue in her political life if it reveals new
details or draws critical conclusions about her conduct in
Whitewater. For the president, it becomes a legacy issue. But
Clinton may have far more than legacy issues to deal with. In the
end, Ray will get the last word, not on Whitewater, but on whether
to seek criminal charges against Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal after Clinton leaves office next year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Even if Clinton isn't charged in the Lewinsky scandal, is
that the end of it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably not. Ray's office is likely to write a final report
describing the basis for any decision not to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who gets the last word in any final report?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Clintons' lawyers do. They will be given the opportunity
to file written rebuttals that will accompany any public release of
a report by a federal appeals court that appoints independent
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Prosecutors have taken six years to investigate Whitewater.
What took them so long?
</P>
<P>
   A: Three reasons. First, new evidence kept surfacing, such as
Mrs. Clinton's long-sought law firm billing records which first
revealed her legal work on a fraud-riddled land development south
of Little Rock, Ark. Second, prosecutors ''turned'' a major figure
in the scandal, Jim McDougal, who had refused to cooperate until a
jury convicted him of 18 felonies. It was McDougal's cooperation
that led prosecutors to a new dimension in Whitewater -- a loan of
$27,000 inside McDougal's S&AMP;L in then-governor Clinton's name. The
president's lawyer has suggested Clinton knew nothing about the
loan. Three, the White House in a time-consuming move, challenged
the prosecutor's efforts to get notes of White House lawyers'
conversations with Mrs. Clinton. After a drawn-out court battle,
the prosecutors got the notes. Ray said the process ''complicated
... our access'' to evidence and prolonged the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did Ray make his Whitewater statement now?
</P>
<P>
   A: The prosecutor said at the beginning of this year that he
wanted to have a prompt resolution of pending matters in the
investigation. Ray has stuck to a fairly rigorous schedule in
closing out various aspects of the investigation. While closing out
Whitewater without bringing charges against the Clintons, Ray's
action has not met with universal approval among Democrats. Sen.
Carl Levin, D-Mich., for example said Ray should have filed his
findings under seal with the judges who appointed him. Ray
''violated the fairness that the law intends,'' Levin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Not Charged in Whitewater  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, won't
be charged in the Whitewater investigation, but the country hasn't
heard the last of the saga that has its origins in a failed
Arkansas land deal in the 1980s.
