<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ewing traded to Sonics in four-team deal  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing's 15-year career with the Knicks ended Wednesday
night when New York sent him to Seattle in a four-team, 12-player
trade also involving the Los Angeles Lakers and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks sent Ewing to the SuperSonics and received Glen Rice
from the Lakers and Luc Longley from the Suns. Among the other
major players moving were Horace Grant from Seattle to Los Angeles
and Chris Dudley from New York to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ''It became clear that he was looking for a change and when he
requested a trade, we respected his request,'' Knicks general
manager Scott Layden said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was important in doing so, however, that we had the ability
to add value, and we believe we have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Various trades involving Ewing and Rice have been in the works
for the past month, including one involving Detroit that fell apart
at the last moment in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, Lakers and Sonics then discussed a three-team deal,
but the Knicks wouldn't pull the trigger because they felt they
weren't getting enough in return.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Suns entered the picture, the talks heated up again.
</P>
<P>
   Several other players were included in the trade to make it work
under league salary cap guidelines. The Knicks got Vernon Maxwell,
Vladimir Stepania and Lazaro Borrell from Seattle and Travis Knight
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   New York also got first-round draft picks in 2001 from the
Lakers and Sonics, and two second-round picks in 2001 from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also get Greg Foster, Chuck Person and Emanuel Davis
from Seattle. Phoenix gets the Knicks' No. 1 pick in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''Getting Patrick accomplishes a big offseason goal of ours,''
said Sonics general manager Wally Walker, adding that 48 trade
scenarios were discussed between the Sonics, Knicks and Lakers.
''Until we got on the conference call with the league this
afternoon, I had no confidence that the deal would get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a free agent, received a one-year offer from the Chicago
Bulls this week. But he wavered on signing it as his agent, David
Falk, tried to broker another deal, and the Bulls finally pulled
the offer off the table Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rice ended up with the Knicks as part of a sign-and-trade
transaction in which he got a multiyear contract from the Lakers
before being shipped immediately to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The trade brings a close to Ewing's career in New York, where he
arrived as the No. 1 pick in the 1985 draft. He was expected to be
the type of franchise player who could bring the Knicks their first
championship since 1973, but it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Sonics have a center who can help them compete with the
better teams in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Patrick's going to come and add us something that we
needed, We needed someone to cope with the Rasheed Wallaces and the
Shaquille O'Neals,'' Seattle's Gary Payton said. ''We hope this is
going to help Vin come back to the player he wants to be. I know
Patrick's going to help our scoring, and it should open up things
for me because a lot of people are going to be worried about
doubling Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's only appearance in the NBA Finals came in 1994 when the
Knicks lost to Houston in seven games. The Knicks made it back to
the finals in 1999, but Ewing was injured and did not play.
</P>
<P>
   ''Patrick is one the hardest working, most loyal players I have
ever been around,'' New York coach Jeff Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have told him more than once that he is a champion even if
he hasn't won a championship. He practiced and played like a
champion every day he was here. Seattle is fortunate to get a
player of his talent and character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 0200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Targets Criticize Probe  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES JEFFERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansans are saying ''I told you so''
one more time after Independent Counsel Robert Ray decided
President Clinton and wife Hillary Rodham Clinton should not be
indicted in the Whitewater investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a hollow victory for more than a dozen state residents
who were caught and convicted in the limelight of a national
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In wrapping up the most expensive independent counsel inquiry in
history, Ray, who succeeded Kenneth Starr, issued a statement
Wednesday saying there was ''insufficient'' or ''inconclusive''
evidence to warrant charges against the president and first lady in
the six-year, $52 million probe.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McDougal, a former Clinton business partner who spent 18
months in jail for refusing to cooperate with Starr, lashed out at
the investigation and criticized Ray for what she said was a
lukewarm absolution of the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ''After they've gathered all of the evidence, all the documents
they said they couldn't find, all the testimony they said they
didn't have -- I answered every question at my trial -- they still
cannot come back as men and say there is no guilt there,'' McDougal
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said of Starr, ''I believe him to be a man of no
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   McDougal and her ex-husband, the now-deceased Jim McDougal, were
the Clintons' partners in the failed 1978 Whitewater land deal that
lent Starr's wide-ranging investigation its name. The McDougals and
then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker were convicted of bank fraud May 28, 1996,
in the first Whitewater trial.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen other Arkansans were charged in the probe, largely with
white-collar crimes unrelated to the Clintons' business dealings
that were the original focus of the probe. Most pleaded guilty to
misdemeanor or felony charges ranging from misapplication of a
federal loan to defrauding the federal Small Business
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mike Huckabee said investigations conducted under the
Whitewater banner exposed criminal activity and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the process left scars on not just the guilty but many
innocent people as well,'' Huckabee said. ''Everyone feels relieved
this chapter of our state's history has concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Herby Branscum Jr. and Robert Hill, owners of the Perry
County Bank in Perryville, were accused of illegally funneling
money from their bank to Clinton's campaigns for governor and
president.
</P>
<P>
   They were acquitted on the most serious charges, and the jury
deadlocked on the several others. Starr eventually dropped the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should never have been started,'' Branscum said, accusing
Starr of using heavy-handed tactics to bully innocent Arkansans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think these people who worked for Kenneth Starr know
what fairness is about. I wasn't treated fairly and I don't think
anyone else who had to deal with those people were treated
fairly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McDougal was sentenced to two years in prison but did not
begin serving the time for 18 months -- first she had to serve time
for contempt for refusing to answer questions about Clinton before
the Whitewater grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   She completed her contempt term March 9, 1998, and began her
Whitewater prison term. The following June, a judge reduced her
prison term to time served because she had health problems. She
still faced a criminal contempt indictment for again refusing to
talk to a grand jury about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She was acquitted of an unrelated California embezzlement charge
in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, a federal jury deadlocked on the two criminal
contempt charges and acquitted McDougal on an obstruction of
justice charge. The judge declared a mistrial on the contempt
charges. Starr's office opted not to retry the case. Her former
husband died in a federal prison in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal now cares for her ailing parents in Camden while not
traveling the country lecturing about women in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Meeting Angers Czech Merchants  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREA LORINCZOVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Economic leaders are gathering to
boost global business and share the wealth more fairly, but don't
tell that to merchants in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Tight security and fears of violent protests have prompted many
to close their doors -- or even get out of town -- as the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and G-7 finance
ministers come to town over the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''No business goes on here,'' grumbled Ladislav Malovec, owner
of two shops that will close for 10 days beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Malovec angrily shook his head when asked how much money he
expects to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to talk about it,'' Malovec said, standing behind
the counter in his empty grocery.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on the street, there were few ordinary citizens seen
among the armed police who were too busy patrolling the area to buy
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Stores along 15 streets around Prague's Congress Center, where
the world economic leaders will meet, were either closed Wednesday
or preparing to close.
</P>
<P>
   Global prosperity may be the goal, but Prague's fourth district
is being turned into a heavily guarded, temporary ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   Signs posted on doors and windows said: ''Due to the so-far
unpredictable situation during the IMF meeting the store will be
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   They were referring to the possibility of mass protests that
could turn the annual meetings of the IMF and World Bank into
embarrassing repeats of the violence that broke out during last
year's disastrous meeting of the World Trade Organization in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A disparate group -- including human rights activists,
environmentalists, anarchists, communists and far right-wing
skinheads -- has announced plans for protests during the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Many shop owners are clearly concerned their stores could be
attacked by demonstrators who call economic globalization a huge
threat to ordinary people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sell paint, cleaning products and other things that are
flammable, so it will be safer to be closed,'' said Martina
Zarubova, a shop assistant in a household goods store that will
shut for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to salvage whatever business can be saved, employees
posted a sign out front urging customers to ''Shop in time!''
</P>
<P>
   But many, if not most, had already vacated the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Those citizens who chose to stay face more problems from tight
security.
</P>
<P>
   Police have put the neighborhood under heavy guard, forcing
residents to show identifications as they come and go. Friends and
relatives must be accompanied by someone who can prove residency.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who has a car can't park here. Residents have had to
move their vehicles elsewhere for security reasons, said Helena
Glesgova, a spokeswoman for the fourth district. But officials have
opened the way for silver Audis, Skodas or minivans that will
transport IMF and World Bank delegates in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Glesgova said shop owners would be free to supply their stores
during the night.
</P>
<P>
   That brought little comfort.
</P>
<P>
   On the window of the Jas meat shop, workers used pink paint to
write on the glass: ''due to the IMF meeting we were not allowed to
supply the store.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Seeking Edge With Energy Issue  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Faced with growing concern over soaring prices
for heating oil this winter, Al Gore is trying to turn the energy
issue to political advantage, accusing oil companies of unnecessary
''profiteering'' and promising government action if prices continue
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning Thursday on Maryland's Eastern Shore, the Democratic
presidential candidate was outlining a plan for ''energy
independence'' and taking another swipe at oil company profits that
have more than doubled in the first half of the year compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   To address the concerns, Gore was expected to call on Congress
to approve $400 million in additional federal assistance to help
poor people pay to heat their homes this winter. The Energy
Department predicts heating costs will be a third higher this year
than last.
</P>
<P>
   He also was prepared to make clear that the Clinton
administration was ready to make oil available from the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve if OPEC failed to increase production.
Administration sources said late Wednesday that a decision on
whether to tap the reserve was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shortly, I suspect the president will make some decision,''
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson told Northeast members of
Congress, adding that ''all options remain on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters Wednesday that the OPEC ''have to keep their
promise to raise production and reduce the world oil price.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do not ''we can act. We should act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries twice this
year has boosted oil production, but the actions have failed to
stem rising prices that hit a decade-high of $37.80 a barrel on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Republican presidential rival, George W. Bush, said the
Clinton administration -- including Gore -- should ''be held
accountable for a failed energy policy'' that has thwarted domestic
oil production and failed to confront OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a town meeting Wednesday in Pennsylvania what he would
do under the circumstances, Bush said he would ''use our diplomatic
leverage'' against OPEC and increase domestic drilling, including
in a protected arctic wildlife refuge in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge is believed to harbor about 10 billion barrels of
recoverable oil, but environmentalists strongly oppose its
development. Even if drilling were approved today, it would take a
decade or more before oil actually would flow from the refuge,
according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   As he did last summer when gasoline prices soared to $2 a
gallon, Gore on Wednesday singled out oil company profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to look carefully at profiteering that has caused big
oil company profits to go up two to three times just as Americans
are paying skyrocketing price increases at the gas pump,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 major oil companies during the first eight months of this
year earned a total of $15.5 billion, nearly triple the profits
during the same period in 1999 when oil prices were depressed,
according to the Energy Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Profits totaled $10.3 billion in the second quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   Independent oil producers also fared well, with earnings up 259
percent in the second quarter, compared with the same period a year
earlier, according to the EIA.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the populist theme of recent weeks, Gore portrayed
himself as the man ''who is going to fight for people even when it
means standing up to big oil companies and foreign oil.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never hesitated to do that,'' Gore insisted, alluding
to Bush's past as a former oilman and his running mate, Dick
Cheney, a former executive of a major oil supply company.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast lawmakers for some time have urged the administration
to draw from the government's emergency reserve, which holds nearly
600 million barrels of crude.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was said to favor using the reserve as leverage to try to
persuade OPEC to increase production. One option under review
within the administration is an oil ''swap'' that would inject
additional supplies into the market without actually selling
government oil.
</P>
<P>
   The government would put oil out for bid. Companies would be
lent a certain amount of oil from the reserve and would replace it
at a future date when oil prices, presumably, would be lower. No
money would be exchanged, but more oil would be put into the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department already is trading oil from the reserve in
exchange for heating oil. It hopes to stockpile 2 million barrels
of heating oil in a new Northeast storage facility by the end of
October for use in case of a supply disruption this winter. About
500,000 barrels of heating oil already is in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
