<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvians Divided on President  </HEADLINE>
By BILL CORMIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peruvians remain deeply divided over the rule
of President Alberto Fujimori and fearful about the uncertain
position of the country's politically powerful military, filling
the capital's streets with rallies both for and against him.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of anti-Fujimori demonstrators lit tire fires and
protested outside his home Wednesday night, burning an effigy of
the president's unpopular spy chief, a shadowy figure at the center
of a bribery scandal that is forcing Fujimori to end 10 years in
power.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting slogans, about 500 students and labor activists called
for Vladimiro Montesinos to be prosecuted. They also demanded
Fujimori step down immediately. As the scandal surfaced last week,
the president stunned Peruvians by announcing he would call new
elections and cut short his own term.
</P>
<P>
   Only the night before, Fujimori had greeted thousands of
sympathizers outside the Government Palace, scaling the towering
gates to show himself still firmly in charge. Mocking the
president, one demonstrator Wednesday night dressed in mime's white
facepaint, donned jail stripes and hung off the gate, waving to the
crowd with a sign on his neck reading ''No to Corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of riot police guarded the palace but did not intervene
as students lit tire fires outside the downtown Lima building and
kicked some toward lines of officers, sparks flying.
</P>
<P>
   One major lingering political question in a country with a long
history of military coups was the position of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori assured Peruvians that military commanders remain loyal
to him and that there was no danger of rebellion over his decision
to fire Montesinos. But the military remained ominously silent
Wednesday -- in sharp contrast to the swift, rock-solid support they
have expressed for him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful military has played a leading role during
Fujimori's decade-long rule, shoring up his government in times of
protest against his often-tough measures. Peru's military last
ruled from 1968 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But Montesinos has hand-picked all six of Peru's regional
commanders and former presidential candidate Alejandro Toledo said
there was a tug of war between the two men over control of the
army.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Fujimori apparently does not have the power to fire
Montesinos,'' said Toledo, who withdrew from May's presidential
runoff after accusing Fujimori of planning to rig the results.
</P>
<P>
   Peru's ombudsman, Jorge Santistevan, urged the armed forces to
make a public declaration of support for Fujimori. Opposition
leaders also expressed concern about the silence.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats who are following the situation closely said they
believe the government has the military under control and there is
no danger or a coup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montesinos is out as we understand it. He is not exercising
his functions. He's fired,'' said a high-ranking Western diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts and retired army generals questioned that
view.
</P>
<P>
   ''Montesinos is using all his fire power to avoid being
dismissed. The question is whether he is willing to carry this game
to an armed confrontation against the government, including other
sectors of the military,'' said political analyst Mirko Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   Even people in the street had doubts about Fujimori's ability to
oust Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in a dangerous moment. The generals could still try a
coup. Their hands are as dirty as Montesinos' hands,'' said Gabriel
Cochan, a 38-year-old unemployed electrician.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fujimori's approval rating soared after his
announcement Saturday that he would not run for office in the new
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The independent polling firm CPI said 62.5 percent of Peruvians
agreed with that decision. At the same time, CPI said Fujimori's
approval rating had soared to 59.1 percent, his highest rating this
year. The poll of 400 Peruvians had a margin of error of five
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation last year was 3.7 percent and guerrilla insurgencies
have been largely dismantled by Fujimori, winning him considerably
support, particularly in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents continued to pressure Fujimori to show he was in
control by dealing decisively with Montesinos, his former top
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo demanded that Montesinos face justice after last week's
release of a videotape that showed the national intelligence chief
allegedly bribing an opposition lawmaker to join Fujimori's ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape's airing unleashed the political crisis, and
Montesinos has not been seen in public for days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
