<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clintons Not Charged in Whitewater Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, won't be charged
in the Whitewater investigation, but the country hasn't heard the last of the
saga that has its origins in a failed Arkansas land deal in the 1980s.
Whitewater first came to public attention in the 1992 presidential campaign amid
questions about the failure of a savings and loan owned by the Clintons'
Whitewater business partners, Jim and Susan McDougal. On Wednesday, Independent
Counsel Robert Ray announced that there was ''insufficient'' evidence to prove
beyond a reasonable doubt that either one of the Clintons committed a crime in
Whitewater.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Seeking Advantage With Energy Issue
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Faced with growing concern over soaring prices for heating
oil this winter, Al Gore is trying to turn the energy issue to political
advantage, accusing oil companies of unnecessary ''profiteering'' and promising
government action if prices continue to rise. Campaigning Thursday on Maryland's
Eastern Shore, the Democratic presidential candidate was outlining a plan for
''energy independence'' and taking another swipe at oil company profits that
have more than doubled in the first half of the year compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescued Cubans Arrive in U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- The remaining eight Cuban survivors of a plane crash
in the Gulf of Mexico were brought to Key West for medical evaluation Wednesday.
A ninth survivor was already being treated at a Key West hospital for head and
neck injuries. The decision to bring the remaining survivors ashore was based on
their medical conditions, said a Coast Guard spokesman. He said one woman has
cuts on her hands and legs, another woman may have a broken collarbone, and the
third woman may have a broken rib.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Hostage Asks for Halt in Assault on Rebels
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- In the first confirmation that he was still
alive, an American held hostage by Muslim rebels appealed to the Philippine
government Wednesday to halt its military assault aiming to free him and other
captives and resume negotiations. The interview was the first word from Jeffrey
Schilling, a Muslim convert from Oakland, Calif., since thousands of troops
launched an assault on Saturday on remote Jolo island to rescue him and 18 other
hostages held by Abu Sayyaf rebels.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Missile' Fired at Britain's MI6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Unknown attackers fired a ''small missile'' at the
headquarters of Britain's MI6 intelligence agency in central London late
Wednesday, causing an explosion on the eighth floor, police said. The blast
caused limited damage and no injuries at the 10-story structure at the heart of
Britain's intelligence abroad. Witnesses reported hearing two explosions, large
enough to send up a plume of white smoke and to rattle buildings across a
railway.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
38 Iraqis Detained on Mexican Border
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Agents held 38 Iraqis at the Mexican border Wednesday after
small groups of them tried to walk into the United States without visas, INS
officials said. Mexican police detained about 150 others in a Tijuana hotel
room. A letter from someone claiming to represent the group said the Iraqis are
Chaldeans, who are Christian, who were tired of waiting in Tijuana for
permission to enter the United States and decided to present themselves en masse
at the border, according to an INS official speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge: Government Not Liable for Waco Deaths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- A federal judge cleared the government of any wrongdoing
in the deaths of 80 Branch Davidians during the 1993 standoff with federal
agents at the cult's compound. U.S. District Judge Walter Smith's ruling mirrors
the conclusions an advisory jury and Special Counsel John Danforth reached in
July.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Thursday morning. The Nikkei shed 21.10
points toa end the morning session at 16,437.21.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Davenport Withdraws From Olympics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Defending champion Lindsay Davenport withdrew
Thursday from the Olympics because of a foot injury, ending a bid by the U.S.
team for a medals sweep in women's tennis. Further tests were planned to
determine whether the injury is a stress fracture, and Davenport said she could
be sidelined the rest of the year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Send Ewing To Sonics, Get Rice From Lakers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Patrick Ewing's 15-year career with the Knicks ended
Wednesday as New York sent him to the Seattle SuperSonics in a four-team,
12-player trade also involving the Los Angeles Lakers and Phoenix Suns. The
Knicks received Glen Rice from the Lakers and Luc Longley from the Suns.
</P>
