<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastwood Defends His Hotel in Suit  </HEADLINE>
By BRIAN BERGSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A woman accusing Clint Eastwood of
violating the Americans with Disabilities Act at a historic hotel
he owns testified that she sent him two letters about the problem
but got no response.
</P>
<P>
   Diane zum Brunnen, 51, who suffers from muscular dystrophy and
uses a wheelchair, is seeking unspecified damages in a federal
lawsuit against Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   The actor-director acknowledges his Mission Ranch in Carmel was
not fully accessible to wheelchairs, but says he was not given a
fair chance to improve it before he was sued.
</P>
<P>
   Zum Brunnen began testifying Wednesday while about 15 people in
wheelchairs watched in the courtroom and protested outside. Her
testimony was scheduled to continue Thursday, possibly followed by
Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   With Eastwood watching from the defense table, zum Brunnen and
her husband both testified they had dinner at Mission Ranch in 1995
and considered staying there. They said they later wrote Eastwood
to complain that there were no ramps at key places and that the
wheelchair-accessible guest room was $225 a night, when other rooms
were as low as $85.
</P>
<P>
   That letter went unanswered, the zum Brunnens said, so she sent
a second to Eastwood via certified mail. The letter was refused.
</P>
<P>
   The zum Brunnens say they again had dinner at Mission Ranch on
Jan. 21, 1996, and discovered that the accessible bathroom for the
restaurant was more than 200 feet away, through the parking lot;
and the main office could be reached only by climbing two stairs.
They sued a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood attorney Chuck Keller challenged inconsistencies in the
couple's stories that he said made it impossible to prove whether
they even visited Mission Ranch that day.
</P>
<P>
   John Burris, zum Brunnen's attorney, said Eastwood has spent
$6.7 million on renovations since buying it in 1986 but neglected
to improve wheelchair access, which would have cost less than
$20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rules were violated at a time when it was easy to follow
the rules,'' Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Tuesday why he didn't settle the case, Eastwood, 70,
said, ''In my opinion, you settle when you're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In May Eastwood testified before Congress in support of a bill
requiring that property owners be notified of alleged Americans
with Disabilities Act violations before they are sued.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice's site on the ADA:
http://www.usdoj.gov/crt/ada/adahom1.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
