<HEADLINE> GAO Questions Contract Awards  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators say a federal
agency that guarantees pensions when employers go bankrupt awarded
$40 million in contracts to a friend of one of its executives.
</P>
<P>
   But Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.'s executive director says the
agency has investigated and cannot substantiate the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Bennie Hagans, the agency's insurance
operations director, had a close relationship with Integrated
Management Resources Group, a company owned by one of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hagans' actions ... demonstrated a lack of impartiality
with respect to IMRG and created the appearance of improperly
influencing the award of the two contracts we investigated,'' the
General Accounting Office report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the matter would be referred to the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The report was to be released Thursday at a joint hearing of the
Senate Special Committee on Aging and the Senate Small Business
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   PBGC Executive Director David Strauss says the allegations have
been investigated for the past three years. ''No one has been able
to substantiate any allegations of misconduct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., created in 1974, protects the
retirements of 42 million workers against the bankruptcy of their
employers. Strauss was expected to testify at Thursday's hearing,
which was expected to examine the agency's service to pensioners,
including contracting mismanagement and lack of computer security.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said between April 1997 when IMRG chief Myrna
Cooks started her company and October 1997, Hagans made 34 calls to
her home, where IMRG was based. Cooks told GAO officials those
calls concerned personnel problems at her old company but could not
provide examples.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hagans was similarly unable to explain the contents of the
many telephone conversations that he had had with Ms. Cooks,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said a Maryland bank officer with whom IMRG
tried to get a loan contacted Hagans. In his notes from the
discussion, the bank officer said ''Mr. Hagans had said he 'was a
very big fan of Myrna's (Ms. Cooks) and politicked within the
agency for her company to receive the bid,''' the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagans told the GAO he did not remember speaking to the bank
officer but if he had, it ''may look wrong'' and in hindsight it
would have been ''bad judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
