<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Spending Measure  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's lopsided rejection of a routine
spending bill that contains a pay raise for members of Congress is
hindering Republican efforts to resolve their budget battle with
President Clinton and hit the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   By 69-28, the Senate voted down the near-$33 billion measure
Wednesday, which would finance the Treasury Department, several
small agencies and Congress itself. It would also repeal the 3
percent federal tax on telephone service. Democrats said Clinton
would have vetoed the bill because it shortchanged the Internal
Revenue Service and counterterrorism programs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure will eventually be revived, perhaps as part of a
larger spending package. But for now, the vote underlined the
complicated task GOP leaders face as they race to finish the 11
remaining domestic and foreign aid spending bills for fiscal 2001,
which begins Oct. 1. Only two spending measures, both financing
military programs, have become law.
</P>
<P>
   With this November's elections for control of the White House
and Congress looming, Republican leaders would like to complete the
work by mid-October. They know that task will mean acceding to
demands by Clinton -- and lawmakers of both parties -- for billions
in added spending.
</P>
<P>
   In another illustration of the difficulties ahead, lawmakers
meeting in a basement room of the Capitol narrowed some differences
over an $18 billion measure financing the Interior Department and
cultural programs, but still found themselves with big gaps.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed to provide $105 million for the National Endowment
for the Arts, the controversial agency's first budget increase
since 1995, when Republicans took control of Congress. And
Republicans ended efforts to block proposed administration rules
ending snowmobiling in many national parks.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure would provide just $420 million of the $970
million Clinton wants to buy new federal, state and local park
lands. And there were disputes over other environmental provisions,
such as one exempting New Hampshire's White Mountains from policies
aimed at limiting logging.
</P>
<P>
   All 43 voting Democrats plus 26 Republicans voted against the
Treasury measure.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained about GOP leaders' decision to speed
consideration of the bill by voting on a version approved earlier
by the House, without allowing amendments. Republicans said
Democrats were just looking for an excuse to slow Congress' work,
thereby embarrassing the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democrats wanted to slow the process down,'' Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., said of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Further adding to legislators' discomfort, the bill would clear
the way for members of Congress to receive a $3,800 pay raise in
January, a 2.7 percent increase that would put their salaries at
$145,100.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., an author of the overall
bill, said many members facing re-election were ''scared to death''
to vote for the pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   ''That little nothing increase made them go limp in the spine,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Underlining that issue's political sensitivity, of the 29
senators running for re-election, 21 voted against the bill and
three did not vote. Many lawmakers who initially voted for the
measure changed their votes to ''no'' after it became apparent that
the bill would be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Senate approval would have sent the measure to the White House.
The House approved it last Thursday by a narrow 212-209 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was actually a combination of two spending bills,
combined by GOP leaders in hopes of streamlining the budget
process. One contained $30.4 billion for the Treasury Department
and smaller agencies, the other $2.5 billion for Congress' own
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill provided $8.6 billion for the IRS, about $300 million
less than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The bill, H.R. 4516, can be found at http://thomas.loc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
