<HEADLINE> Navy Seeks Relatives of WWII Pilots  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jack Parlier was itching to fly.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of March 25, 1944, from Alaska's Attu Island at the
westernmost tip of the Aleutian chain, the 22-year-old Navy weather
specialist finally got his chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took off, and he never came back,'' recalls Paul Carrigan,
a retired Navy weatherman who briefed Parlier that day on what to
expect aboard a Ventura PV-1 patrol bomber whose mission was to fly
east through the darkness to Japan's northern Kuril Islands, bomb
the target and return to Casco Field on Attu.
</P>
<P>
   The dark-of-night mission, flown repeatedly in the final two
years of World War II to tie down a portion of the Japanese air
force, became known as the Empire Express, and the men who flew it
were called ''bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Parlier's job was to chart and photograph weather formations
along the route, where storms were so hazardous that only one of
the five aircraft from Parlier's squadron completed the mission
that night.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other four, one crashed shortly after takeoff from Attu,
two failed to reach the target and had to turn back, and Parlier's
vanished. It was not until a Russian historian, Alla Paperno, told
U.S. officials last year that wreckage of an American bomber had
been found that the mystery began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, U.S. officials traveled to the crash site on the
slope of a volcano on Russia's Kamchatka Peninsula and confirmed
that the wreckage was Parlier's plane. It may have been hit by
Japanese anti-aircraft fire and attempted to make an emergency
landing on a Soviet air strip at nearby Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some human remains were found, but U.S. forensics specialists
plan to return to the site next summer for a full-scale excavation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a real high priority,'' Roland Lajoie,
chairman of the U.S.-Russia Joint Commission on POW/MIAs, said this
week. The retired Army general led the expedition to the crash site
in August.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Navy is trying -- without much success -- to
find relatives of Parlier and the six other crewmen. Dave Greco,
head of the casualty assistance branch at Navy Personnel Command,
said Monday the Navy wants to find the nearest possible relative to
let them know that remains have been found.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the Navy may ask for blood samples from a relative in
the maternal blood line so that mitochondrial DNA testing can be
done on bones recovered from the crash site, Greco said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Navy has been contacted by family members of two of
the crewmen -- co-pilot Lt. John W. Hanlon Jr. of Worcester, Mass.,
and mechanic Donald Graham Lewallen of Omaha, Neb. Searches of
public records, telephone directories and the Internet have failed
to turn up relatives of the others, Greco said.
</P>
<P>
   The other men are the pilot, Lt. Walter S. Whitman of
Philadelphia, and three enlisted men: Samuel Leslie Crown Jr. of
Columbus, Ohio; Clarence Crome Fridley of Manhattan, Mont., and
James Stephen Palko of Superior, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Parlier not only had never flown in combat, he had never flown,
period, Carrigan recalled in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was eager, charged up, looking forward to it,'' he said.
Carrigan supervised Parlier at the weather office on Attu and
remembers him as ''a neat kid, bright-eyed, apple cheeks, full of
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Parlier's home of record was Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Will Swinney, a retired Navy radioman who was a member of the
same squadron on Attu, VB-139, said planes and ships were sent to
try to rescue the lost crew but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Swinney says he still has an uneasy feeling that not all members
of the crew died in the crash. Tokyo Rose, the voice of Japanese
propaganda broadcasts to Allied troops during the war, was heard to
report after the plane went missing that Japan had possession of
the flight jackets of Whitman, the pilot, and Hanlon, the co-pilot,
Swinney said. Others heard slightly different versions, but all
said Tokyo Rose referred to Hanlon as ''Moose'' Hanlon, which was
his nickname, instead of his given name, John.
</P>
<P>
   ''How would they know that?'' Swinney wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Relatives of these missing servicemen can call
the Navy Casualty Office at 1-800-443-9298.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Navy bombing squadron VB-139 at
http://www.vpnavy.com/vp139.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
