<HEADLINE> Lawmakers: Money For I-495 Is Short  </HEADLINE>
By GARRETT THEROLF
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Maryland members of Congress said Wednesday
they doubt they will get all of the federal money in next year's
budget needed to complete a $1.9 billion project for relieving a
round-the-clock bottleneck on the major East Coast highway from
Canada to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers told members of Maryland's state legislature they
still hope to win just enough money to continue work on replacing
the six-lane Woodrow Wilson drawbridge on the Interstate 95/495
beltway just south of Washington with a 12-lane span.
</P>
<P>
   So far Congress has appropriated $900 million for the project
and Maryland and Virginia have agreed to spend another $200 million
each.
</P>
<P>
   While contending that the bridge is ''national responsibility''
rather than a state one, Rep. Connie Morella, R-Md., said there is
widespread bipartisan opposition in Congress to picking up all of
the remaining tab.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Barbara Mikulski and Paul Sarbanes, both D-Md., said they
were trying to win enough money in an appropriations bill to keep
the project going. The two states, however, have not made clear how
much that would be, an aide to Sarbanes said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chairmen of the relevant subcommittees are not sympathetic
to it,'' Sarbanes said. ''I can't tell how that's going to come out
..., the amount of time left is extremely limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the Maryland side of the bridge over the Potomac
River has already begun after Sen. John Warner, R-Va., won a waiver
from the Environmental Protection Agency this summer. Courts had
ruled that under the federal Clean Air Act, all of the funds had to
be in place before ground could be broken on the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
