<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Effects of Calif. Casinos Weighed  </HEADLINE>
By KIMBERLY LAMKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Representatives from 17 area American Indian
tribes sat down with county officials to discuss the environmental
and economic effects of a major expansion of tribal gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes want to add nine casinos to a county that's about
4,200 square miles. Three tribal casinos already operate in San
Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   All the county's American Indian lands are in unincorporated
areas and few have the roads, water service and sewers necessary to
accommodate large commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The county Board of Supervisors wants to ensure that
environmental and infrastructure problems are handled fairly. Also
of concern for local officials is providing adequate fire and law
enforcement services.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's extremely important to begin this dialogue with the
tribes now,'' said Board of Supervisors Chairwoman Dianne Jacob.
''Discussions on improving their infrastructure before putting
these developments in unincorporated areas could prevent
environmental and infrastructure problems of large proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Tribal leaders say gambling centers will not be added in a way
that harms the environment. They say the facilities will help
provide for the needs of their tribes, and bring money and new jobs
to San Diego County as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tribal governments have the opportunity to be self-sufficient
through commercial activity, mainly gaming,'' said Rincon San
Luiseno Band Chairman John Currier. ''I hope the county will
emphasize the positive regional economic benefits of what is
happening within reservation communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 1A, passed by California voters in March, allows a
federally recognized tribe to operate slot machines, lottery games
and card games on its lands, provided the governor has approved a
gambling compact with the group.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting was the first between the county officials
and representatives from all 17 tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob has proposed that one person be appointed to serve as a
tribal liaison for the county board, and that a committee of two
supervisors and a few tribal leaders meet again in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Indiana Affairs:
http://www.doi.gov/bureau-indian-affairs.html
</P>
<P>
   National Congress of American Indians: http://www.ncai.org
</P>
</TEXT>
