<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groups Working To Get Out the Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- From the nation's largest civil rights
organization to the construction industry's trade association,
interest groups will spend the remaining weeks before Election Day
trying to water the grass roots instead of flooding the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Though these organizations still intend to spend record amounts
on issue advertisements, they also are diverting substantial sums
of money away from television and pouring it into efforts to
organize supporters and get them out to vote on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''The money's important in campaigns, but you need to get people
out to vote and get activated,'' said Bill Spencer, vice president
for government affairs for Associated Builders and Contractors, the
construction trade group and traditional Republican ally. ''You can
spend the money, but unless they go to the polls, it's not going to
help you much.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurring these groups to act is the fact that control of the
White House and both houses of Congress are up for grabs, plus the
possibility that the next president may appoint several Supreme
Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a crucial election. There's so much at stake. We
wanted to use all the modern tools and so we decided to put on this
extra effort,'' said Julian Bond, the veteran civil rights leader
who heads the board of directors of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, whose members traditionally
support Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP has formed a new organization -- the NAACP National
Voter Fund -- with a $9 million budget to target black voters in 12
key states.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the new group has registered 21,000 voters and signed
up 2,345 volunteers to make phone calls, knock on doors and do
other grass-roots organizing, Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, organized labor showed how successful such a
program could be.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than spend millions of dollars on advertising, the unions
went into key congressional districts, distributed literature, made
phone calls and got their members to the polls. On Election Day,
Democrats gained seats in the House and broke even in the Senate,
reversing a decades-old trend that saw the party occupying the
White House losing seats in off-year elections.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the AFL-CIO has committees in 71 congressional
districts in 25 states to distribute literature and buttonhole
union members.
</P>
<P>
   ''The person-to-person contact is the most effective way to
communicate our message,'' said Daniel Weiss, political director of
the Sierra Club, an environmental organization that has allocated
$8 million for the fall campaigns, half of it to be spent on
grass-roots organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Television is an important communication tool, but it's a
rather impersonal one,'' Weiss said. ''The other side may have the
big checkbooks but we have the shoe leather. That is more
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, which traditionally supports Democrats, has its
own scorecards to distribute in 20 congressional districts, plus
field organizers to help get out the vote. In the last three weeks
before Election Day, it plans to have people in 50 districts.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy has worked in the past. The AFL-CIO said 76
percent of union members who received election-related information
voted for the labor-backed candidate in 1998, as compared with 58
percent who did not receive any information. So the labor
federation hopes to double the percentage of its members who
receive fliers from the union to 22 percent from 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The business community, a traditional Republican ally, also is
working the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Builders and Contractors suggests its 22,000 member
companies invite candidates to construction sites so their 1
million employees can meet them. It also is urging company
executives to include literature in payroll envelopes comparing the
voting records of the trade group-endorsed candidates and their
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Other suggestions from the construction trade group to its
members: Contribute the wood and labor needed to build candidate
booths for county fairs; conduct voter registration drives at work;
and give employees a shorter work day on Election Day so they can
go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the nation's largest business
lobby, plans to blanket 3 million business owners with mailings
promoting its endorsed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber also has joined several other powerful business
groups, including the National Restaurant Association, National
Association of Manufacturers and Business-Industry Political Action
Committee, to provide business owners and executives with
information they can use to urge their colleagues and employees to
support pro-business candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: NAACP National Voter Fund: http://www.naacpnvf.org
</P>
<P>
   Associated Builders and Contractors: http://www.abcv2k.org
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club: http://www.sierraclub.org
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Chamber of Commerce: http://www.uschamber.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
