<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of Sept.
24-30:
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1954, ''The Tonight Show'' made its debut on NBC with host
Steve Allen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, ''The Beverly Hillbillies'' premiered on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, the Beach Boys made their first appearance on ''The Ed
Sullivan Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1964, ''The Bullwinkle Show'' premiered on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, John Lennon and Paul McCartney appeared on ''The David
Frost Show'' to talk about the virtues of transcendental meditation
as taught by the Maharishi Mahesh Yogi.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, ''60 Minutes'' made its debut on CBS, with reporters
Harry Reasoner and Mike Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, ''Abbey Road,'' the Beatles' last studio album, was
released in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, ''Goat's Head Soup'' by the Rolling Stones went gold;
the Stones admitted it wasn't their favorite album.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the movie version of ''The Rocky Horror Picture Show''
had its premiere in Westwood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, ''The Love Boat'' premiered on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the Stray Cats were signed to Arista Records in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, ''Cheers,'' with Ted Danson and Shelly Long, made its
debut on NBC. It ran until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, ''Murder, She Wrote,'' starring Angela Lansbury,
premiered on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, ''Crocodile Dundee'' opened in theaters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1986, the Beatles song ''Twist and Shout'' re-entered
the pop charts after it was featured in the movies, ''Ferris
Bueller's Day Off'' and ''Back to School.'' It eventually rose to
No. 23.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Motion Picture Association of America announced the
creation of the NC-17 rating, replacing the X rating for films with
mature subject matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 0759 </TRAILER>
