<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Keep Slipping  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower Thursday amid lingering
gloom on Wall Street about corporate profits and higher oil prices.
The drop threatened to end a high-tech rally from the previous two
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again unloaded stocks of companies that issued
warnings of disappointing profits. Even a report by one of Wall
Street's most prominent analysts that the economy remains quite
favorable for the markets failed to halt the early selling.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Dow opened down 14.80 at
10,673.12.
</P>
<P>
   Broader indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite index
fell 31.53 to 3,865.91 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 6.57
at 1,444.77.
</P>
<P>
   In a report Thursday, Goldman Sachs analyst Abby Joseph Cohen
said she believes high oil prices, the weak European currency and
corporate profit concerns ''will be short-lived.'' She also
reiterated that U.S. economic conditions remain quite favorable,
particularly in the areas of improved productivity and government
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But her words didn't calm investors, who have become accustomed
to stock market declines in September.
</P>
<P>
   With third-quarter earnings season just a few weeks away and
increasing signs that the U.S. economy is slowing, investors have
been punishing stocks whose companies fail to meet their
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Tire maker Goodyear fell $2.44 to $18.56 after the company
warned its quarterly earnings would be sluggish because of higher
oil prices and the weak euro, Europe's chief currency.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 2.50 to 518.93.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.89 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.15 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 1.25 percent, and France's CAC-40 was off
2.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
