<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 8; Nasdaq Falls 25  </HEADLINE>
BC-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0043,0479   
Stocks mixed Thursday on lingering concerns about corporate
profits   
Eds: UPDATES trading.
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Thursday amid lingering gloom
on Wall Street about corporate profits and higher oil prices. The
uncertainty threatened to end a high-tech rally from the previous
two sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again unloaded stocks of companies that issued
warnings of disappointing profits. Even a report by one of Wall
Street's most prominent analysts that the economy remains quite
favorable for the markets failed to halt the early selling.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Dow moved up 7.40 to
10,695.32.
</P>
<P>
   But broader indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index
fell 24.63 to 3,872.81 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 6.30
at 1,445.04.
</P>
<P>
   In a report Thursday, Goldman Sachs analyst Abby Joseph Cohen
said she believes high oil prices, the weak European currency and
corporate profit concerns ''will be short-lived.'' She also
reiterated that U.S. economic conditions remain quite favorable,
particularly in the areas of improved productivity and government
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But her words didn't calm investors, who have become accustomed
to stock market declines in September.
</P>
<P>
   With the third-quarter earnings reporting season just a few
weeks away and increasing signs that the U.S. economy is slowing,
investors have been punishing stocks whose companies fail to meet
their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Tire maker Goodyear fell $2.81 to $18.19 after the company
warned that its quarterly earnings would be sluggish because of
higher oil prices and the weak euro, Europe's chief currency.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter traded down $9.19 to $86.75 after the
brokerage firm's third-quarter earnings failed to meet Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The market's search for sure bets meant that even companies that
beat analyst estimates were vulnerable. Investment bank Lehman
Brothers fell $5.69 to $138.75, primarily on profit-taking, a day
after its quarterly profits trounced analyst expectations by 62
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in search of profits were more enthusiastic about
Hertz. The car rental company was up $7 at $31.25 on news that Ford
was interested in buying the stock of the company that it doesn't
already own.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-8 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 138.08 million
shares, slightly ahead of the 135.25 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was off 0.20 at 519.91.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.89 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 2.15 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 1.25 percent, and France's CAC-40 was off
2.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
