<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Bunim-Murray, Reality TV Not New  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Unless you look a little closer, it seems the
garbage collector missed a stop in the lobby of the Bunim/Murray
Productions office.
</P>
<P>
   A colorfully decorated cereal box stands on display. There's a
roll of toilet paper filled with neat handwriting. A globe. A
champagne bottle. Even a graffiti-filled door is propped against a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   It's a messy tribute to the ingenuity of MTV viewers, who sent
each of those items -- along with thousands of videotapes and
letters -- as applications to join ''The Real World,'' which is
produced here.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its ninth season, ''The Real World'' is an elder
statesman in the reality television business. Watch this series
about self-obsessed twentysomethings crammed in a house after an
episode of CBS' ''Big Brother,'' and you'll think you've stumbled
upon Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   More mailbags of pleading notes and tapes are due soon, since
MTV just signed on for two more years. ABC has also requested more
episodes of Bunim/Murray's ''Making the Band'' and another series,
''Love Cruise,'' is being readied for Fox this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're excited that reality is finally getting its due, that
networks are taking it seriously,'' said Jonathan Murray. ''There
were many years when network presidents, quite honestly, weren't
interested in what we had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Murray and partner Mary-Ellis Bunim are in the middle of a
gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   Bunim, a former soap opera producer, and Murray, who made news
documentaries, stepped in when MTV decided in the early 1990s that
it could not live on music videos alone. The network wanted its own
soap opera but found it too expensive, so Bunim and Murray
convinced them there's enough drama in real lives.
</P>
<P>
   There's actually much that's unreal about college-age youths
staying in luxurious homes in such locales as Hawaii, Miami or San
Francisco. But viewers are eager to see how combustible characters
interact at a naturally tumultuous point in their lives. Through
this season, ''The Real World'' has the unusual distinction of
growing in the ratings each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you think about the generation that watches TV now, they've
grown up not only on 'The Real World' but on Oprah and Jerry
Springer,'' said Brian Graden, MTV's programming president.
''They're used to real people parading their dramas out in front of
people as entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's also the first generation to come of age with mass
distribution of video recorders. Some people are surprised that
it's taken off, but for the people who are 25 and 30 and even 35
like myself, we grew up watching this kind of TV. Our parents
watched dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the memorable characters on ''The Real World'' include
the obnoxious Puck from San Francisco; Pedro Zamora, who died of
AIDS at 22; and Ruthie, the 21-year-old Hawaiian who was sent to
rehab last season when her drinking went out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bunim and Murray wear out VCRs trying to find the right mix
of people each season.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're only as good as your cast, and we spend a lot of time
choosing our cast,'' Bunim said. ''We don't scrimp on that time.''
</P>
<P>
   They also spend three to five months after the series is filmed
crafting a story, much like the producers of ''Survivor'' this
summer. For every foot of film, 200 feet are left in the cutting
room. Writers are used, not to concoct a story, but to look at the
mounds of material and see the stories hidden inside.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fundamental, centuries-old storytelling is really universal,
no matter what form it is, and they brought it to reality,'' Graden
said. ''Watching paint dry, as you do on other shows, really isn't
that interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did somebody mention ''Big Brother'' again?
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question that we could have done it better. But,
whatever ... ,'' Bunim said, her voice trailing off.
</P>
<P>
   The producers said they were consulted on ''Big Brother,'' but
didn't want to get more involved, believing that wouldn't be fair
to MTV because the premise was so close to ''The Real World.'' They
can see the same mistakes most CBS viewers notice every day --
lackluster cast, ugly home and contrived situations.
</P>
<P>
   ''What they do that we can't do is they manipulate the people,''
Bunim said. ''They're so worried about how it's going that they, on
a daily basis, are throwing things in to stir the pot. We learned
early on that it just makes people paranoid.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunim/Murray also produces ''Road Rules'' for MTV, which places
a group of youngsters in a bus for a series of adventures and
competition. They mix and match casts from both shows for spinoffs
and even sell a video: ''The Real World's Greatest Fights.''
</P>
<P>
   They're looking to diversify, making a movie for CBS starring
Valerie Bertinelli, and are producing a series for ABC about the
start-up of an Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Either Murray or Bunim will spend much of the fall on a ship to
supervise ''Love Cruise.'' The series brings eight men and eight
women together on a boat, who get together in separate groups each
episode to vote one member of the opposite sex off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   They're trying not to run ragged as the reality TV boomlet stays
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going down the road, a lot of it is going to cancel each other
out,'' Bunim said. ''We think our method of storytelling will
prevail and sustain long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   GOING DIGITAL: The Public Broadcasting Service has reached an
agreement with Time Warner Cable to have digital signals of public
TV stations carried on cable systems in Time Warner markets. PBS
considers this an important step in future expansion plans; it
hopes to eventually have several separate channels offering the
service's programming. The agreement is contingent upon 80 percent
of public TV stations in Time Warner markets agreeing within 45
days. The stations on Time Warner cable systems reach 12 percent of
American television households.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   David Bauder can be reached at dbauder''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
