<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GAO Questions Contract Awards  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators said a federal
agency that guarantees pensions when employers go bankrupt awarded
$40 million in contracts to a friend of one of its executives.
</P>
<P>
   But Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.'s executive director said the
agency has investigated the charges and cannot prove them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Thursday that Bennie Hagans, the agency's
insurance operations director, had a close relationship with
Integrated Management Resources Group, a company owned by one of
his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hagans' actions ... demonstrated a lack of impartiality
with respect to IMRG and created the appearance of improperly
influencing the award of the two contracts we investigated,'' said
Robert Hast, assistant comptroller general for the office of
special investigations at the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hast said the matter would be referred to the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''Possible contract steering is a serious matter that must be
thoroughly investigated,'' said Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo.,
chairman of the Senate Small Business Committee. ''I believe OSI's
decision to refer this matter to the Justice Department is on
target.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was released Thursday at a joint hearing of the
Senate Special Committee on Aging and the Small Business Committee.
</P>
<P>
   PBGC Executive Director David Strauss said the allegations have
been investigated for the past three years. ''No one has been able
to substantiate any allegations of misconduct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report said between April 1997 when IMRG chief Myrna
Cooks started her company and October 1997, Hagans made 34 calls to
her home, where the new firm was based. Cooks told GAO officials
those calls concerned personnel problems at her old company but
could not provide examples.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Hagans was similarly unable to explain the contents of the
many telephone conversations that he had had with Ms. Cooks,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said a Maryland bank officer with whom IMRG
tried to get a loan contacted Hagans. In his notes from the
discussion, the bank officer said, ''Mr. Hagans had said he 'was a
very big fan of Myrna's (Ms. Cooks) and politicked within the
agency for her company to receive the bid,''' the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagans told the GAO he did not remember speaking to the bank
officer but if he had, it ''may look wrong'' and in hindsight it
would have been ''bad judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., created in 1974, protects the
retirements of 42 million workers against the bankruptcy of their
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Pension recipients complained at the hearing about getting
erroneous payments for hundreds of dollars. But after returning the
checks, they would get tax notices from the Internal Revenue
Service and the pension corporation would reduce their future
payments based on the errant checks. Others said it took years for
the agency to tell them how much pension money they could expect
when they retired.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss said his agency was continuing to make improvements
suggested by the committees and the GAO. ''I'm pleased to report to
you that we have already implemented most of the and we are
following up on the rest,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
