<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reverse for Pentagon in Deutch Case  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Heading off a rare public dispute with the
CIA, the Pentagon changed its explanation of why it took nearly two
years to appraise damage from security lapses by former CIA
Director John Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Until reversing its position Wednesday, the Pentagon had
explained it wasn't able to assess the damage until February
because it lacked access to the unsecured computer files where
Deutch entered defense and intelligence secrets. The Pentagon
position changed after the CIA said publicly earlier in the day
that it offered access to those files in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon blamed the rejection of the offer on its own
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ''It indeed appears an offer was made by CIA investigators to a
DOD investigator in June of 1998 to examine information ... that
the CIA had gathered in its investigation of Dr. Deutch,'' a
Pentagon spokesman, Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, said. ''That offer was
declined by DOD investigators without ever informing senior
leadership within DOD of the offer.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, Quigley declined to say whether the
Pentagon investigator was wrong to decline the CIA's offer without
checking with higher-level officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to second-guess him,'' Quigley said. Later,
however, he referred to the decision as a ''problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said in an interview Wednesday that the Pentagon
investigators declined the offer in 1998 because ''in their
professional judgment, no productive purpose would be served by
starting a separate effort'' parallel to the CIA's own probe of the
Deutch matter. ''Our investigators had confidence in their
counterparts over at CIA.''
</P>
<P>
   CIA spokesman Bill Harlow said Wednesday, ''Our records show
that the CIA did offer them access on June 17, 1998, to the
journals that Deutch was working on. The journals were the parts
that would have been of interest to DOD. We did offer them access
to that at the time. They didn't pick up on it at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlow added that the Pentagon had another chance to act in
August 1999 when it received a briefing on the spy agency's
findings about Deutch's handling of classified information. Defense
officials ''didn't request the underlying documents until February
2000,'' Harlow said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported Monday that internal Defense
Department memos showed that in summer 1998 the CIA urged the
Pentagon to conduct a damage assessment. Those memos, however, did
not mention the CIA's offer to provide the Pentagon with the
computer files relevant to the military secrets.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Quigley said, ''This was all about a potential
compromise of classified information on computers that we did not
have in our possession.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not clear to me how we would have proceeded without
reinventing a lot of the effort that CIA investigators were doing
at the very same time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said the Pentagon began its probe in February, only
after the CIA provided the materials from its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Deutch was a former top Pentagon official before moving to the
CIA, where he was director from May 1995 to December 1996. Now a
professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Deutch has
apologized for his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said he could not estimate when the Pentagon's
investigation would be completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
