<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 49; Nasdaq Down 48  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Thursday amid lingering gloom
on Wall Street about corporate profits and higher oil prices. The
uncertainty threatened to end a high-tech rally from the previous
two sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again unloaded stocks of companies that issued
warnings of disappointing profits. Even a report by one of Wall
Street's most prominent analysts that the economy remains quite
favorable for the markets failed to halt the selling.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading, the Dow moved up 48.83 to 10,736.75, a
shift away from the downward momentum of the past few sessions.
</P>
<P>
   But broader indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index
fell 48.22 to 3,849.22 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 5.82
at 1,445.82.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got some stocks that are up and pushing the Dow higher,
but in general the market remains down,'' said Barry Berman, head
trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. ''It's the end of the quarter and
right now the concerns are oil prices and earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors did boost Hertz up $7.19 to $31.44 on news that
Ford was interested in buying the stock of the car rental company
that it doesn't already own.
</P>
<P>
   Most other stocks fell. With the third-quarter earnings
reporting season just a few weeks away and increasing signs that
the U.S. economy is slowing, investors have been punishing stocks
whose companies fail to meet their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Rising oil prices also have investors worried. The price of a
barrel on crude on the New York Merchantile Exchange was $36.33,
down from the $37 range it reached in recent days, but still at
levels not seen in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Tire maker Goodyear fell $2.63 to $18.38 after the company
warned that its quarterly earnings would be sluggish because of
higher oil prices and the weak euro, Europe's chief currency.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, fears of weakening in the wireless market sent
Ericsson Telephone down $1.75 to $16.25. Sprint PCS, which fell
nearly 19 percent Wednesday after it warned of below expectations
earning, continued to fall, dropping $3.06 to $29.94.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter traded down $9.81 at $86.13 after the
brokerage firm's third-quarter earnings failed to meet Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The market's search for sure bets meant that even companies that
beat analyst estimates were vulnerable. Investment bank Lehman
Brothers fell $4.38 to $140.06, primarily on profit-taking, a day
after its quarterly profits trounced analyst expectations by 62
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Even a report by Goldman Sachs analyst Abby Joseph Cohen stating
that high oil prices, the weak euro and corporate profit concerns
will be short-lived failed to calm inevstors. She also reiterated
that U.S. economic conditions remain quite favorable, particularly
in the areas of improved productivity and government policy.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 714.82 million
shares, down from Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was off 4.23 at 517.20.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
