<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Dissidents Suspected of Blast  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The Irish Republican Army
dissidents suspected of blasting the headquarters of Britain's MI6
secret intelligence service have pursued a long IRA tradition of
striking headline-grabbing targets at crucial moments in Northern
Ireland peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket attack late Wednesday came on the eve of an important
election testing Protestant opinion in Northern Ireland. It appears
to be the latest sign two shadowy splinter groups, the Continuity
IRA and Real IRA, are determined to resurrect the 27-year campaign
IRA commanders abandoned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents oppose the 1998 Good Friday accord that allowed
the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party to join a new Protestant-Catholic
administration in Northern Ireland. The dissidents have resumed
high-profile attacks in London this year, placing bombs on a train
line and a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, dissident attacks simultaneously undermine Sinn Fein
and harden attitudes within the Protestant majority. Protestants
are almost evenly split over the merits of sharing power with Sinn
Fein, a key issue in Thursday's special British Parliament election
in a predominantly Protestant district of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams led his party into
political talks three years ago, he has struggled to seek
compromise with Protestants while minimizing disillusionment and
splits in his own ranks.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Adams and Sinn Fein chief negotiator Martin
McGuinness confronted their most outspoken critic, Mickey McKevitt,
who was then the IRA's ''quartermaster general'' responsible for a
network of secret arms dumps, according to Sinn Fein and other
well-placed sources.
</P>
<P>
   McKevitt rejected a process that required Sinn Fein to renounce
''armed struggle,'' to accept that Northern Ireland's political
union with Britain would remain, and to persuade IRA leaders
eventually to unveil their weapons bunkers to international
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   McKevitt resigned to forge a group that proclaimed itself to be
the ''true IRA,'' soon christened the Real IRA by Irish media. It
built a loose alliance with another group called the Continuity
IRA.
</P>
<P>
   The first dissident car bomb ravaged a mostly Protestant village
the day after Sinn Fein entered the 1997 talks. Two more mostly
Protestant towns were hit in early 1998, apparently in hopes of
provoking the major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, to
demand Sinn Fein's exclusion from the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Phoned warnings to Belfast media, and swift police reaction,
prevented deaths.
</P>
<P>
   No group claimed responsibility, fueling Protestant suspicions
that the Adams-McGuinness leadership sanctioned the destruction,
despite their vehement denials.
</P>
<P>
   Police intercepted other car-bomb ''spectaculars'' days before
the Good Friday deal, and again on the day voters in both parts of
Ireland ratified the peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents blasted a village the day Northern Ireland voters
elected a new legislature. Protestant hard-liners fared well,
cramping the Ulster Unionists' room for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before President Clinton's arrival to push for
progress in 1998, dissidents bombed Omagh. Phoned warnings were
confused and imprecise, and the blast killed 29 people -- the single
worst incident in three decades of ''the troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents held fire throughout 1999, as efforts to form the
power-sharing government stalled over the issue of IRA disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the government got up and running, the IRA
unveiled a few weapons dumps to inspectors, and the dissidents
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the dissidents have recruited more than 100 members --
including a few IRA men paroled from prison as part of the Good
Friday accord.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating a new proficiency, dissidents earlier this month
fired a mortar into a police barracks, a technology perfected by
mainstream IRA engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Recent weapons seizures in the Republic of Ireland and Croatia
indicate that dissidents have purchased weapons through Yugoslav
sources, including compact rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   A fragment of a rocket-propelled grenade found at the scene of
Wednesday's attack indicates such a weapon could have been used in
the strike on the MI6 headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 1544 </TRAILER>
