<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDC: Gonorrhea's Resistance Grows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Gonorrhea is growing more difficult to treat,
building up resistance to two antibiotics, government researchers
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Hawaii, strains of the sexually transmitted disease that
resist fluoroquinolone antibiotics, a common treatment, jumped from
1.4 percent in 1997 to 9.5 percent last year, the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention reported. In Kansas City, Mo.,
gonorrhea resisted a newer antibiotic, azithromycin, in 12 patients
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The government recommends three other antibiotics to treat
gonorrhea, all of them more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Drug-resistant strains of gonorrhea have spread from Asia and
similar resistance in the mainland United States is inevitable,
said Susan Wang, a CDC epidemiologist. Similar resistance in the
1980s rendered penicillin and tetracycline ineffective for treating
gonorrhea.
</P>
<P>
   The disease causes painful, burning urination and a puslike
discharge from the urethra or vagina. The government documented
360,000 cases in the United States in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cdc.gov/nchstp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 1600 </TRAILER>
