<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Case Information of 10 Iranian Jews  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An Iranian appeals court on Thursday reduced the
sentences of
the following 10 Iranian Jews, who had been convicted of spying for
Israel. Defense lawyers said the prosecution's case had relied
solely on confessions made after long periods of detention.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Dani Tefilin, 30: Sentence reduced to nine years. Identified as
the main defendant, he was originally sentenced to 13 years for
membership in an illegal group and cooperation with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Tefilin, a shoe salesman, was the first of the defendants to be
arrested more than a year ago and the first to confess on
television. He said he had traveled to Israel and trained with its
main external spy agency, Mossad. He said Israel had paid him in
installments of $500 in exchange for sensitive information about
Iran, and that his mother, two sisters and a brother live in the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Asher Zadmehr, 54: Sentence reduced to seven years. An
English-language professor, he originally received a 13-year jail
sentence for setting up an illegal spy network and cooperating with
Israel. Zadmehr confessed to having cooperated with Israel and
having assessed and evaluated information before it was sent to the
Jewish state, but he denied forming a spy ring.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Nasser Levihaim, 50: Sentence reduced to seven years. A civil
servant who worked for the state power company, Levihaim originally
was given an 11-year jail term for his admitted leadership role in
the network. Levihaim said his role was to cull the information
gathered by other agents. Levihaim said he was motivated by
ideological reasons and love of the Jewish state, not by money.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Ramin Farzam, 27: Sentence reduced to eight years. A store
clerk, he was originally sentenced to 10 years for membership in an
illegal group and cooperation with Israel. Farzam pleaded guilty to
espionage charges, saying he was paid by Israel to spy but was
caught before he could relay information.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Shahrokh Paknahad, 30: Sentence reduced to five years. A
religion teacher, he was originally sentenced to eight years. He
confessed to spying for Israel. A stalwart of the small Jewish
community in Shiraz, he said he had used his position to recruit
agents. Paknahad said he collected information for sabotage and
gathered military information during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war
while he was performing mandatory military service.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Javid Bent-Yacoub, 42: Sentence reduced to six years. A
shopkeeper, he originally received nine years for membership in an
illegal group, cooperation with Israel and recruitment of new
agents. He said he had traveled to Israel for 45 days in 1993,
where he had met with a Mossad agent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Farhad Seleh, 40: Sentence reduced to six years. An owner of a
textile shop and a religion teacher, he was sentenced to eight
years for membership in an illegal group and cooperation with
Israel. He pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Farzad Kashi, 30: Sentence reduced to six years. A religion
teacher, he originally was sentenced to eight years for membership
in an illegal group and cooperation with Israel. Kashi pleaded not
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Faramarz Kashi, 34: Sentence reduced to three years. A religion
teacher and brother of Farzad, he confessed to spying for Israel
and originally was given a five-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Ramin Nematizadeh, 27: Sentence reduced to two years. A shop
clerk, he was originally sentenced to four years. He confessed in
court he had gathered military information for Israel during his
mandatory army service and sent it to Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
