<HEADLINE> Spanish Councilor Shot Dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANT ADRIA DE BESOS, Spain (AP) -- A town councilor of the ruling
Popular Party was shot to death outside Barcelona on Thursday,
bringing to 13 the number of killings blamed on the armed Basque
separatist group ETA so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Ruiz Casado, 42, was shot once behind the left ear as
he walked to his car in the coastal town of Sant Adria de Besos on
the outskirts of Barcelona, said police. He was shot again in the
head after he fell to the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, two attackers fled the scene in a white
Renault, which was later found nearby, torched to destroy evidence,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The assassination came soon after French and Spanish police
detained 29 suspected ETA members over the weekend, including
Ignacio Gracia Arregui, considered the leader of ETA's military
wing.
</P>
<P>
   A French court put 10 of those suspects -- six Spanish and four
French -- under formal investigation Thursday, judicial sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja said Sunday the
police roundup had caused ''almost irreparable damage'' to ETA
because some of the suspects played key roles in the group's
forgery and logistical operations. But he warned that ETA would
probably seek revenge.
</P>
<P>
   After a particularly bloody summer, Ruiz Casado's death is the
13th this year blamed on ETA, which ended a 14-month cease-fire
last December. The separatist group has claimed 11 of the killings.
It usually claims its attacks several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The escalation of violence could be an attempt by ETA to force
the government into negotiations. One round of talks held during
the cease-fire produced no advances. But the government has since
ruled out talks and insists on combatting ETA with police measures.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz Casado, married with two children, was the fourth town
councilor of Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar's center-right Popular
Party killed so far this year. The other victims included
opposition Socialist party and security force members.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar, who visited Ruiz Casado's widow in Barcelona, called on
Spaniards to ''maintain a tenacious and daily effort and permanent
mobilization'' against ETA.
</P>
<P>
   King Juan Carlos denounced ''ETA's blind terrorism.'' Deputies
in the European Parliament in Strasbourg, who were discussing ETA
violence as news of the shooting came in, held a minute of silence.
</P>
<P>
   The regional government declared two days of mourning and the
balconies and windows of Sant Adria de Besos fluttered with white
sheets marked with black ribbons as stunned friends and relatives
gathered at the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   ETA has claimed the killing of nearly 800 people in its 32-year
campaign for a Basque homeland straddling northern Spain and
southwestern France. Its name is an acronym for Basque Homeland and
Freedom in the Basque language.
</P>
<P>
   An anti-ETA protest has been called in Barcelona for Friday
evening. Tens of thousands of people had already been expected to
march in an anti-ETA rally Saturday to protest the recent
escalation of violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
