<HEADLINE> Gunmen Holding Hostages in Russia  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH INGRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian security forces surrounded a hotel in
southern Russia on Thursday where gunmen held at least four people
hostage and were demanding $30 million and a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Police held off storming the building as they negotiated with
the hostage-takers by mobile phone.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen appeared to have dropped a demand that Russia release
all Chechens being held in prison, and a top government spokesman
said it wasn't clear whether the incident had anything to do with
Russia's war against separatists in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Security agents occupied the first floor of the two-story
building in the southern Russian town of Lazarevskoye, 35 miles
west of the Black Sea resort of Sochi.
</P>
<P>
   But Gherman Ugryumov, a deputy director of the Federal Security
Service, said agents would not storm the building unless they saw
an immediate threat to the hostages' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the situation changes and the lives of the hostages are
threatened, law enforcement agencies will use force,'' he said.
''Negotiations are going on constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports of how many people were involved
in the hostage-taking.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin's envoy to the region, Viktor
Kazantsev, said there were four gunmen and six hostages, while Maj.
Salbi Gerba, the head of the local Interior Ministry branch said a
man who fled the scene said four people were being held by two
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Yastrzhembsky, a Kremlin spokesman, said five people were
being held in a private house that was being used as a small hotel,
and that there were three captors. At least one person escaped by
jumping out a window, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen did not identify themselves, officials said. But
Yastrzhembsky said they were local residents and they were
demanding talks with Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television networks showed police in bulletproof vests
surrounding the three-story house, and armored vehicles parked
outside it. Crowds of onlookers stood on nearby street corners.
</P>
<P>
   Initial negotiations were conducted through a female hostage,
officials said, but officials later passed a mobile telephone to
the gunmen and opened direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-taking came several days before the anniversary of
the start of the latest Russian war in Chechnya. Russian jets
bombed the outskirts of Grozny on Sept. 23, 1999, and troops rolled
into the breakaway republic seven days later.
</P>
<P>
   But Yastrzhembsky said it was too early to draw a connection.
''There are no grounds so far to speak of a Chechen connection,
since the terrorists have not been identified yet,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
