<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army: Chemical Weapons Plant Fixed  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The safety lapses that let a tiny amount of
the nerve gas sarin escape from the Army's chemical weapons
incinerator in Utah have been fixed, officials told a House panel
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The corrective actions we've taken ... will most likely
prevent this type of thing from happening again,'' said Mike Rowe,
manager of the incinerator near Tooele, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   A similar accident would not result in any nerve gas releases at
incinerators being built in Alabama, Oregon and Arkansas, because
those facilities have extra filters and other safety features, Army
officials told the House Armed Services subcommittee on military
procurement.
</P>
<P>
   A jammed incinerator door started a series of equipment problems
and worker errors leading to the sarin leak May 8-9. The leak was
the first reported at the Utah incinerator, which has burned
thousands of tons of nerve gas and other chemical weapons since
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rowe said the amount of sarin released was smaller than a drop
of water, and investigations by the Army and the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention concluded that the release was too
tiny to harm people or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Sarin, the same chemical used in a Tokyo subway attack in 1995
that killed 12, kills by paralyzing the lungs and other vital
organs.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Bob Riley and Sen. Jeff Sessions of Alabama said
the Utah accident lowered their confidence in a similar chemical
weapons incinerator being built near Anniston, Ala. Riley said he
was upset that Army officials had assured him before the accident
that nerve gas could never escape the Utah incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Army has lost a lot of credibility in my eyes,'' Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials and outside scientists told the lawmakers that
destroying the chemical weapons is safer than letting them
deteriorate in storage. Many of those weapons leak, which
occasionally releases nerve gas, mustard gas or blistering agents
into the air, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greatest risk is from the leaks'' from stored weapons,
said John Ferriter, a top official in the Army's chemical weapons
destruction program.
</P>
<P>
   Such leaks have released one million times the nerve gas
released by the Utah accident, said David Kosson, a member of a
National Academy of Sciences group that oversees chemical weapons
destruction.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Army's chemical weapons destruction program:
http://www-pmcd.apgea.army.mil/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Incinerator opponents: http://www.cwwg.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 1704 </TRAILER>
