<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FEMA rejects appeal for aid to flood-damaged Fairfield County  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The Federal Emergency Management Agency
rejected a second request Thursday for aid for flood-damaged parts
of Bridgeport and Stratford.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA said the flood damage was not severe enough to warrant a
major disaster declaration. The agency also said that the damage
does not appear to be greater than what the state and local
governments can handle.
</P>
<P>
   The agency issued similar findings last month. Gov. John G.
Rowland appealed that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland's office said the U.S. Small Business Administration may
be able to offer low-interest loans to homeowners and business
owners damaged by the flood. The Connecticut Development Authority
already has approved below-market loans for people whose property
was damaged in the flood.
</P>
<P>
   The storm dumped torrential rain on the area August 11 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the state found that 260 homes and 30 businesses
were damaged, with downtown Stratford was hit the hardest. At least
24 businesses in Stratford sustained major damage, and many of the
businesses were not insured.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the appeal, a reassessment of the damage was done,
said John Wiltse, the state's director of emergency management.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the state found 471 homes and 61 businesses that were
damaged, but only five of these properties had the kind of major
damage that FEMA is looking for, Wiltse said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel we had a strong case with FEMA, especially after we
reassessed and nearly doubled the numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep Rosa DeLauro, whose district includes Stratford, set up
a meeting with state and local leaders for Friday to discuss what
else can be done.
</P>
</TEXT>
