<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health officials: West Nile virus is here to stay  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARAMUS, N.J. (AP) - Even though cooler weather soon will slow
the spread of the West Nile virus as mosquitoes go into
hibernation, the disease appears to be here to stay because the
insects retain the virus throughout the winter, health officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   State Health Commissioner Christine Grant said New Jersey and
surrounding states will have to deal with the potentially deadly
virus again next year, and probably well beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the nights get colder and we have the first ground frost,
mosquitoes go into hibernation and the risk will lessen
considerably,'' she said during a news briefing on New Jersey's
response to the virus, which has infected two human beings in the
Garden State so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we've also learned that the mosquitoes continue to carry
the virus during the winter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus is transmitted through the bite of a
mosquito that has picked up the virus by feeding on an infected
bird. It was first identified in the Western Hemisphere in
September 1999, causing 62 cases of encephalitis in New York and
seven deaths. This year, there have been 11 human cases in New York
City, including eight in Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Figures released Thursday by the state health department showed
no new human cases over the past week. Test results are being
awaited from 34 people in New Jersey who have shown many of the
symptoms associated with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The only human cases confirmed so far in New Jersey are a
43-year-old man from Jersey City and a 54-year-old man with homes
in Brooklyn, N.Y., and Cliffside Park.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the federal Centers for Disease Control, Dr. Jeffrey
P. Koplan, visited Bergen County Thursday to review the state's
efforts to combat the virus, calling them ''a textbook example'' of
how to deal with a public health threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't fully understand the epidemiology or the full public
health implications of this new virus, but the right things are
being done,'' he said, referring to the state's reporting system,
localized spraying programs and outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 838 crows and one cockatiel have tested positive for the
virus in New Jersey this year out of 1,527 crows that were tested.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials also admitted they're disappointed and somewhat
puzzled over the failure of the so-called ''sentinel chickens'' to
detect the presence of the virus. Blood samples taken weekly from
chickens in all 21 counties have all tested negative for the virus,
even though crows in 16 counties have tested positive for it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne Crans of Rutgers University said the poultry program
was borrowed from Florida, where the caged birds had a good track
record in identifying St. Louis encephalitis, a disease which is
very similar to the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone figured that method would work,'' he said. ''It's
fairly obvious it has not. They are obviously not being bitten by
the mosquitoes carrying the virus, and we can only speculate that
it's a behavioral thing. If I were a mosquito looking for a bird,
I'd look up; the chickens are down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 1732 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0143 </DOCNO>
