<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Salt Ruling Raises Controversy  </HEADLINE>
By NIRMALA GEORGE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A government move to put cheap salt
without iodine back on the market threatens the health of millions
among India's most vulnerable groups, poor children and pregnant
women, health experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from small business lobbies, the government last
week lifted a ban in force for a decade and a half that prevents
non-iodized salt being sold in India.
</P>
<P>
   Health and humanitarian officials immediately slammed the
government move, saying it would seriously affect efforts to
eradicate iodine deficiency in India, so far one of the country's
few public health success stories.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of iodine causes goiter, or the enlargement of the
thyroid glands. It also results in a greater number of miscarriages
in pregnant women and a higher incidence of mental retardation,
deaf-mutism and impaired learning capacities in children.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the controversy, India's health minister, C.P.
Thakur, insisted Thursday iodized salt would continue to be
available throughout the country and announced the government would
subsidize it to make it affordable to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The move came a day after the United Nations Children's Fund
criticized the move to allow non-iodized salts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to drop the ban is likely to have grave
consequences for the health of India's population, especially two
of its most vulnerable groups, young children and pregnant women,''
it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. N Kochupillai, head of Endocrinology at the All India
Institute of Medical Sciences, said the lifting of the ban was ''a
retrograde step which will cause incalculable damage to future
generations of Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   India imposed the ban on non-iodized salt in the mid-1980s after
research conducted over two decades by the Indian Council of
Medical Research showed that people in many parts of the country
were not getting enough iodine in their diets.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has come under pressure from small-scale salt
producers who say their livelihoods are threatened because they
cannot afford to install iodization plants, according to Thakur.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee's Bhartiya Janata Party was
lobbied by its political allies to lift the ban. The Swadeshi
Jagran Manch or Self-reliance Awakening Forum, argued that
multinationals had profited from the ban on non-iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the crossfire Thursday, the government promised to
bring down the price of iodized salt through state subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   But UNICEF, for one, thinks the move will cancel out its efforts
to improve basic health. Its statement called India's salt
iodization program one of the country's most successful public
health interventions.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 per cent of India's 1 billion people currently have
access to iodized salt, but this figure would go down now the ban
on non-iodized salt has been lifted, the UNICEF statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 1733 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shays pushes for moratorium on tribal recognitions  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The federal government should stop recognizing
American Indian tribes for the next six months and investigate the
recognition process, a handful of Republican House members said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., accused the Clinton
administration of letting donations from tribes and supporters of
tribal groups influence the recognition process.
</P>
<P>
   ''The administration is playing fast and loose in this
process,'' Shays said. He refused to give specifics, though he
accused officials from the Bureau of Indian Affairs of selectively
quoting from experts' opinions to support tribal recognitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a plethora of money that is coming into play and that
is distorting the process,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Hanna, a spokeswoman with the Department of the
Interior which oversees the BIA, called Shays' accusations
''absolutely ridiculous.'' Since 1980, 15 tribes have received BIA
recognition and 15 have been turned down, Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been hardly any tribes recognized during the
Clinton administration,'' said Hanna. ''And the ones that have gone
through an extensive process.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently 227 tribes seeking federal recognition - 11
of which are in Connecticut. The Paucatuck Easterns and the Eastern
Pequots, both of which claim descent from the historic Eastern
Pequot tribe, each recently won preliminary recognition from the
BIA. The federal agency is seeking to determine if those groups,
which share a reservation in North Stonington, represent two tribes
or one.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., said there should be a six-month
moratorium on recognitions while the GAO investigates the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to make sure the process is so sound that you can say,
whether you're a member of a tribe or a member of the outside
community, that the process was fair,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a tribe gets federal recognition, it can obtain rights to
build a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said his call for a recognition moratorium is not related
to his opposition to a bid by eight Virginia tribes to win federal
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said a moratorium is useless because it sometimes takes as
long as three years for a tribe to be recognized. However, she said
it's likely there will be a few tribes that are recognized within
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal has also
requested a temporary halt to tribal recognitions, but BIA Director
Kevin Gover told him this week that a moratorium would be
detrimental to the Indian groups seeking federal acknowledgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 1733 </TRAILER>
