<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Not on Self-Sufficient Track  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite more riders, Amtrak is not on track to
free itself from federal operating subsidies by a deadline set by
Congress, a government audit released Thursday found.
</P>
<P>
   The report by Transportation Department Inspector General
Kenneth Mead concludes that ''without major corrective action,''
the national railway will not achieve operating self-sufficiency by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   If Amtrak fails to meet the deadline, Congress could vote to
liquidate the corporation that has overseen intercity passenger
rail since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The report also questions Amtrak's decision to spend capital
funds to expand service and introduce new routes rather than to pay
for ''minimum needs'' like track repair. The inspector general's
office predicts a shortfall of $91 million next year in funds for
minimum needs.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the report is in striking contrast to Amtrak's
consistently upbeat reports of financial progress. Just last week,
Amtrak announced it had registered its best summer ever and expects
to break the all-time yearly record of 22.2 million passengers, set
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Mead's report does not dispute that claim but provides a more
complete picture by including information on expenses, not just
revenue and riders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although ridership and revenue trends are positive,'' the
report says, ''increases in labor costs, depreciation and train
operation expenses have fueled continued growth in operating
expenses'' of 6.9 percent in 1999 and 7.3 percent in the first nine
months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general forecasts that Amtrak will lose $1.4
billion more than it anticipates from 2000 through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Mead's office estimates Amtrak's cash loss in 2000 will be $521
million, the lowest since 1992. But it says Amtrak must reduce its
cash loss to $266 million in 2003 to meet Congress' mandate, and
that will be possible only by ''limiting the growth in Amtrak's
expenses over the next three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak does not have to eliminate its cash loss entirely because
the government will continue to pay some of its costs, like
equipment depreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak released a statement agreeing ''that strong efforts will
be necessary to achieve operational self-sufficiency, as mandated
by Congress. We believe we're up to that challenge, and that our
recent business successes demonstrate our resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials hope the report's emphasis on a shortage of
capital funds prompts Congress to pass legislation authorizing the
railway to raise $10 billion over 10 years for new high-speed rail
corridors throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak maintains it will reach self-sufficiency in 2002, a year
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Mead will testify Tuesday at a Senate Commerce Committee
oversight hearing on Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Inspector general's report: http://www.oig.dot.gov/audits.htm
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak: http://www.amtrak.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
