<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy identifies defendant as man who molested him  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A 10-year-old boy in a courtroom
witness box calmly pointed to a former teacher Thursday and said
the man had molested him in his own bed, then borrowed a
smiley-face pillow and bedded down on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he'd seen defendant Steven Nowicki, the boy said,
was ''in my room'' on New Year's Day 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki looked directly at the witness as the boy identified him
but glanced away for most of his 3&AMP;frac12; hours of testimony in
Westchester County Court.
</P>
<P>
   The former Dobbs Ferry Middle School teacher is accused of
molesting the boy and his older brother after their father,
thinking him drunk, invited him to ''sleep it off'' following the
family's New Year's Eve party.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, in a button-down shirt and a blazer, held a microphone
in his hand and often squeezed his eyes shut as if to concentrate
before answering the prosecutor's questions. Not until the last
question of his cross-examination did he lose his composure,
choking up when the defense focused on his uncertainty over who
turned on a bedroom light.
</P>
<P>
   In gentler questioning by Assistant District Attorney Lisa
Linsky, the boy, who was 8 at the time, said he'd gone to sleep
quickly after the excitement of being allowed to stay up past
midnight to see the new year in.
</P>
<P>
   He testified in clinical detail about being awakened first by a
noise, then again by a man touching and licking him.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said, ''Stop,'' but got no response, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt scared,'' he testified. The man was bigger and
stronger, and the boy felt ''he would just throw me back'' if he
tried to get up. ''I thought he would kidnap me,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After some time, the boy said, the man climbed a ladder to his
older brother's upper bunk.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could not see the man's face in the dark and didn't
realize who it was until the man opened the bedroom door to leave
and light came in from the hallway. He knew it was Nowicki, the boy
said, ''by the shape of his hair on the back of his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki returned later, the boy testified, and said, ''Hi,
boys.'' His brother fled to his parents' bedroom and Nowicki asked
for a stuffed animal to sleep on, he said. The younger brother gave
him ''a yellow circle thing with a happy face on it,'' and Nowicki
lay on the floor with his head on the pillow, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the boy's father came in and told him to join his mother
and brother, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When defense lawyer John Mangialardi went through the incident
on cross-examination, the boy told the story differently, leaving
out the entire encounter between him and the man in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man ... hadn't touched you?'' the lawyer asked. Then the
boy said, ''He was touching me. Then he stopped and went up the
ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangialardi also brought out that the boy was neither physically
injured nor threatened and had not always mentioned his fear of
being kidnapped. The defense lawyer also pointed out
inconsistencies between the boy's testimony Thursday and his
previous comments to police, hospital personnel and a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Nowicki, 37, of Hastings-on-Hudson, who was the older brother's
fifth-grade teacher, is accused of sodomy, sexual abuse and
endangering children. If convicted he could be sentenced to up to
25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro attended part of the court
session, and the defense attorney complained afterward that she had
been ''making comments out loud,'' including one critical of him.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Judge Mary Smith to remind Pirro about ''courtroom
decorum.'' The judge said she hadn't heard any comments and doubted
the jury had.
</P>
<P>
   David Hebert, a spokesman for Pirro, said she ''did not make any
comments while she was in the courtroom today. ... This is nothing
more than an underhanded defense tactic to detract from the
testimony of the young boy today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
