<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sick Nuke Workers Petition Congress  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sick weapons plant workers begged lawmakers
Thursday to work out their differences and approve compensation for
people who contracted diseases building the nation's nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Ray of Lucasville, Ohio, a 40-year uranium enrichment plant
employee, held a voice synthesizer to his throat so he could
describe working without protective clothing or radiation
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Workers were kept in the dark about the hazards they faced,''
said Ray, who suffers from a rare bone cancer and had his larynx
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even to this day, we don't know what we confronted,'' he told
the House Judiciary Subcommittee on Immigration and Claims.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Orick, an ailing former weapons plant worker from Knoxville,
Tenn., said workers have been ''left out in the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not right that we should have to come here to plead for
a bill to pass. We're not asking for the moon. We're just asking
for some help,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring the Energy Department reversed 50 years of federal
policy by declaring that workers injured or killed by weapons-plant
exposure be compensated. The agency proposed minimum lump sum
payments of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators are meeting to try to work out a
compromise. Among the issues being discussed are the compensation
amount, which diseases will be covered and whether health benefits
would be included.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it doesn't pass now, it will be years,'' Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson told the committee. ''A lot of these workers will
lose hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Slaughter of Las Vegas said he has silicosis, a
lung-clogging disease, from his work at the Nevada Test Site boring
tunnels where nuclear devices were to be detonated.
</P>
<P>
   ''No respirator protection was provided,'' he said. ''The dust
was so thick, you couldn't see your hand in front of your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Clara Harding poignantly described her husband Joe's slow death
after years of working at the Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant in
Kentucky, which enriched uranium for use in nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was so proud of getting a job like that, working for the
government on such an important mission,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But then came sores that wouldn't heal; mysterious internal
injuries that led surgeons to remove a large part of his stomach;
and fingernail- and toenail-like growths on his palms, the bottoms
of his feet, his knee caps, knuckles, wrists and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   Too sick to work by the age of 50, she said her husband was
turned down for disability retirement and fired from his job as a
chemical operator. He died in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ''DOE killed my husband,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to workers, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, predicted
passage this year of a national compensation program.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is broad-based support in Congress to compensate the
workers,'' he said. ''I think it ought to be done sooner rather
than later, and I think before the end of this Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill numbers are HR 675, HR 3418, HR 3478, HR 3495, HR 4263,
HR 4398, HR 5189 and SB 2519
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bill texts: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department's Radiation Exposure Compensation Program:
http://www.usdoj.gov/civil/torts/const/reca/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department: http://www.doe.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
