<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge upholds $27 million jury award in Yale medical malpractice case </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A judge on Thursday upheld a multimillion
dollar jury award to the estate of a man whose parents sued Yale
University after he suffered brain damage and went blind following
surgery at Yale-New Haven Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in March 1999 awarded $27 million to the parents of Billy
Jacobs, who claimed that doctors were negligent and performed
unnecessary surgery on their son in November 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, then 17, had been recovering from injuries he suffered
in a car accident when William and Arlene Jacobs of Wappingers
Falls, N.Y. brought him to Yale-New Haven because of recurring
fevers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a medical malpractice case involving truly horrifying
injury,'' New Haven Superior Judge Jon C. Blue wrote in a 36-page
decision. ''Under these circumstances, the jury's award of $27
million in damages, while anecdotally the highest personal injury
award in Connecticut legal history, is fair but not extravagant.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Jacobs, now 30, is legally blind, mentally retarded and
can walk only short distances with assistance. William Jacobs quit
his job as a deputy sheriff after the surgery so he could care
full-time for his son who is confined mostly to a bed and
wheelchair at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The clients are relieved and they've been through an ordeal
which comes after many, many years,'' said the Jacobs' attorney,
Michael Koskoff of Bridgeport. ''Their life is one of incomparable
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said Thursday that Yale planned to appeal the
decision in a higher court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are obviously disappointed with Judge Blue's decision since
we continue to believe that we have solid grounds for setting aside
the jury's verdict in this case,'' Yale-New Haven said in an
official statement. ''We look forward to presenting these important
issues to Connecticut's Supreme Court or Appellate Court and remain
confident that the appellate courts will ultimately agree with us
that the jury's verdict in this case was defective, erroneous and
excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the accident, Billy was a healthy high school senior who
enjoyed dancing and worked two jobs, said Koskoff. He aspired to
become an X-ray technician.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Yale-New Haven said Billy Jacobs had a ruptured
aorta. Chief cardiologist Dr. John Elefteriades decided to operate
on Nov. 15, 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Koskoff said Billy never had a hole that required surgery, only
a small tear of the ''intima,'' or inner layer, of his aorta.
</P>
<P>
   ''The skill with which the operation was conducted was a
disputed fact in this case,'' Blue wrote. ''The results of the
surgery were disastrous. A massive hemorrhage developed during the
application of a clamp, and Billy Jacobs lost enormous quantities
of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, the hospital claimed that some of Billy's
injuries were caused by the earlier car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were killed in the Oct. 26, 1986 accident in
Wappingers Falls, including Billy's 15-year-old brother,
Christopher. But Koskoff said Billy had had successful surgery at
another hospital to repair injuries he received in the car accident
- including a lacerated bowel and diaphragm - and was recovering
when he sought treatment at Yale-New Haven for his fevers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Yale filed several post-trial motions, including
requests to set aside the verdict and for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision Thursday, Blue denied all the motions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 1746 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Torricelli-backed ad targets supporter of Torricelli-backed bill  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - As a senator representing New Jersey, Democrat
Robert Torricelli proposed helping a home-state pharmaceutical
company extend its patent on the allergy drug Claritin.
</P>
<P>
   But as chairman of the Democratic Party's Senate campaign
effort, Torricelli helped fund an advertising campaign criticizing
Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., for supporting the very same idea.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's dueling roles have prompted cries of hypocrisy. An
Ashcroft spokesman called the ad fraudulent. The Missouri
Republican Party responded with an ad accusing Ashcroft's
challenger, Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan, of ''assaulting the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli said Thursday he supports the legislation he
introduced on behalf of Schering-Plough Corp. and disagrees with
the theme of the anti-Ashcroft ad.
</P>
<P>
   But he chose not to block the ad, which was paid for by the
Missouri Democratic Party with funds provided by the Torricelli-led
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The DSCC was not created exclusively to advance the interests
of New Jersey or to represent my views,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ad assails Ashcroft for cosponsoring ''special
legislation for Claritin's New Jersey manufacturer to keep cheaper,
generic varieties off the market.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ashcroft's bill means consumers pay more and the company makes
billions,'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also criticizes Ashcroft for accepting a $50,000
contribution from Schering-Plough to a campaign committee he
controls. Schering-Plough gave the same amount to the DSCC on May
26, 1999, just one day before Torricelli introduced the bill to
help the company pursue a patent extension. Torricelli says the
timing was a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, who has won acclaim from his party for raising
record amounts for the campaign effort, said the ad ''represents
the position of the Democratic Party of Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he is in ''an awkward position,''
affiliated with a political ad that condemns his own legislative
cause. He said he expects to find himself in the same position
again soon, when the DSCC goes after Republican senators for
supporting tax cuts. Torricelli has broken with Democrats to
support some tax-cut proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's Claritin bill would let Schering-Plough petition
the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office for three years of additional
patent protection on grounds that the Food and Drug Administration
took an excessively long time to approve the use of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties have blocked efforts to attach the
Claritan language to must-pass spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Donnell, a spokesman for Madison, N.J.-based
Schering-Plough, responded to the ad flap by saying, ''We think
it's unfortunate that a measure which is designed to take issues of
patent inequities out of politics should become the subject of
political campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Food and Drug Administration approved a
six-month extension for Schering-Plough's exclusive marketing of
Claritin. That means a less expensive version of the drug cannot be
introduced before December 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the six-month extension could mean an extra $1
billion in sales before Claritin must compete with a cheaper
generic pill. It may also help Schering-Plough launch a
next-generation Claritin medicine before a generic can erode its
market share.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.schering-plough.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dscc.org
</P>
</TEXT>
