<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 78; Nasdaq Falls 69  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mixed Thursday amid lingering
gloom on Wall Street about corporate profits and higher oil prices.
The uncertainty ended a two-day rally in the high-tech sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 77.60 at 10,765.52, a
shift away from the downward momentum of the past few sessions. But
broader indicators were lower. The Nasdaq composite index fell
68.57 to 3,828.87 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was off 2.29 at
1,449.05.
</P>
<P>
   Investors again unloaded stocks of companies that warned of
disappointing profits. Technology and brokerage firms were among
the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   That dynamic is all but guaranteed to continue Friday following
an announcement by Intel after the close of Thursday's session; the
world's largest chip maker said it expects third-quarter revenues
to fall below earlier expectations. After falling $1.58 to $61.48
during the regular session, shares of Intel plunged another $11.48
to $50 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of other high-tech companies also fell in the after-hours
session. Microsoft, which finished regular trading down 6 cents at
$64.19 on the Nasdaq Stock Market, fell an additional $3.56 to
$60.63. Cisco Systems finished the day down $2 at $61.13, then fell
$3.94 to $58.50 in the after-hours session. Dell Computer initially
dropped 63 cents to $37.94 Thursday, then fell $4 to $33.94 after
the Intel announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's selloff in the technology sector came despite a
report by one of Wall Street's most prominent analysts that the
economy remains quite favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the end of the quarter and right now the concerns are oil
prices and earnings,'' said Barry Berman, head trader for Robert W.
Baird &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, investors did boost Hertz up $7.38 to $31.63
on news that Ford wants to purchase all of the remaining stock in
the car rental company that Ford doesn't already own.
</P>
<P>
   Most other stocks fell. With the third-quarter earnings
reporting season just a few weeks away and increasing signs that
the U.S. economy is slowing, investors have been punishing stocks
whose companies fail to meet their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Rising oil prices also have investors worried. The price of a
barrel on crude on the New York Mercantile Exchange was $36.33,
down from the $37 range it reached in recent days, but still at
levels not seen in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Tire maker Goodyear fell $2.88 to $18.13 after the company
warned that its quarterly earnings would be sluggish because of
higher oil prices and the weak euro, Europe's chief currency.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of a weakening in the wireless market sent Ericsson
Telephone down $1.58 to $16.42. Sprint PCS, which fell nearly 19
percent Wednesday after it warned of below expectations earning,
continued to fall, dropping $3 to $30.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter traded down $6.50 at $89.44 after the
brokerage firm's third-quarter earnings failed to meet Wall Street
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The market's search for sure bets meant that even companies that
beat analyst estimates were vulnerable. Investment bank Lehman
Brothers fell $2.94 to $141.50, primarily on profit-taking, a day
after its quarterly profits trounced analyst expectations by 62
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Even a report by Goldman Sachs analyst Abby Joseph Cohen stating
that high oil prices, the weak euro and corporate profit concerns
will be short-lived failed to calm inevstors. She also reiterated
that U.S. economic conditions remain quite favorable, particularly
in the areas of improved productivity and government policy.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers 8 to 5 on the New York
Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume came to 1.3 billion
shares, down from Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was off 7.08 at 514.35.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.89 percent.
Germany's DAX index was down 1.22 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell
1.29 percent, and France's CAC-40 was off 2.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
