<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would end statute of limitations for homicide, manslaughter lawsuits </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Prosecutors have no time limit when
searching for justice in a murder. Families do.
</P>
<P>
   That's why advocates for victims' rights applauded the unanimous
vote Thursday by the Senate to eliminate legal time limits for
families looking to bring lawsuits after a homicide or
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation now goes to Gov. Christie Whitman. If she signs
the bill, New Jersey's two-year statute of limitations for lawsuits
would be history.
</P>
<P>
   Victim advocates say grief-stricken families don't think to file
lawsuits in time. Or they are told by prosecutors not to pursue
civil cases during criminal trials, supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say the bill gives families the opportunity to collect
damages not just from defendants, but others. In cases where people
are killed during holdups, families could sue store owners who
didn't provide security.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's for the children really. Surviving parents just don't do
that. They don't sometimes file these lawsuits, whether they are in
shock or ill-advised,'' Kathy Garcia, director of South Jersey
Survivors of Violent Crime, said.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure becomes law, it would be the second in response
to the murder of Joan D'Alessandro, a 7-year-old raped and killed
as she delivered Girl Scout cookies in April 1973.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey passed ''Joan's Law'' in 1997, which denies parole to
anyone serving a life sentence for a violent crime that results in
the death of a child younger than 14. A federal version requires a
minimum of life imprisonment with no parole for anyone who commits
a violent crime resulting in the death of a child.
</P>
<P>
   It was a family inheritance Joseph McGowan, who was convicted of
killing Joan D'Alessandro, collected while in prison that prompted
this latest measure, bill sponsor John J. Matheussen, R-Gloucester,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemarie D'Alessandro, the girl's mother, learned of the recent
windfall but was prevented from filing a lawsuit, Matheussen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She wanted to collect not only for the loss of her daughter in
civil damages, but he was using the money to fund his appeals while
he was in prison,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill number S-1125 passed the Assembly by a 78-0 vote on June
29.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitman does sign it into law, New Jersey would join a
growing number of states that allow families to sue years after a
murder, said Jim Ferguson, director of the National Crime Victims
Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho recently changed its law to allow lawsuits filed up to one
year after a defendant finishes a criminal sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's pretty darn close to saying there isn't a limit,''
Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal cases usually have no time limit for charges, civil
cases should enjoy the same benefit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're not going to have a statute of limitations in a
criminal proceeding, where what's on the line is a defendant's
freedom or his life, then it makes sense to have it where there's a
lot less at stake for a defendant,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday also passed another bill sponsored by
Matheussen to expand civil liabilities for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   That action would allow parents, children, spouses and siblings
of illegal drug users to sue drug dealers. Bill S-621, now heads to
the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   States sue tobacco companies and gun manufactures for selling
legal goods, so it make sense to allow people to seek damages from
those that push illicit materials, Matheussen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to accept the liability, not just the criminal
liability, but the civil liability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other criminals, drug dealers often have assets that can
be seized, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bills available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
