<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two judges quit, protesting assignments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Two Superior Court judges in Essex County
quit this week after they were reassigned to handle landlord-tenant
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Murray Simon and Harry Margolis, both veteran jurists,
said the assignments were not suited to their experience.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, 80, and Margolis, 72, are in semiretirement and currently
work on a per-diem basis. Judges have a mandatory retirement age of
70 but often serve on recall after that age.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this is the way you treat judges who are on
recall and working gratuitously much of the time,'' Margolis told
The Star-Ledger of Newark in Thursday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Assignment Judge Joseph A. Falcone said he assigned Margolis and
Simon to pick up the landlord-tenant caseload temporarily because
one of the two judges who handled those cases recently was moved to
the family division and he has about a dozen judicial vacancies.
Falcone said he could not tell the judges how long the assignments
would last.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have nothing but the highest regard for these two judges,''
Falcone said. ''I'm sorry we couldn't work something out.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Margolis had both been on the bench since the early
1970s and both spent several years as presiding judge in chancery
court, a prestigious assignment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
