<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First lady attacks Lazio's ''happy talk'' view of upstate New York  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - In this careworn industrial city, Hillary
Rodham Clinton attacked her U.S. Senate opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio,
on Thursday for attempting to ''dismiss with happy talk'' upstate
New York's prolonged economic troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be one of the people who helps get us out of the
woods and not get further lost in the morass, and he doesn't have
any plan to do that,'' said the first lady, pledging to make
revitalization of the upstate economy her ''No. 1 priority'' if
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks at a Rotary Club luncheon honed in once more on a
theme that re-emerged during a debate here last week when Lazio,
the Republican congressman from Long Island, said he rejected the
notion that ''somehow the upstate economy is on its knees. It's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   In her latest television ad aimed at upstate viewers, Mrs.
Clinton stresses the need to bring ''targeted economic help'' to
the upstate economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among ''the cold hard facts that some would have us ignore or
paper over or try to dismiss with happy talk,'' she said, are job
growth that lags nearly every other state in the country and the
migration of 170,000 people ages 20 to 29 out of upstate New York
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are just 13 metropolitan areas nationwide that lost a
greater portion of their residents than Buffalo, and three of those
13 were upstate neighbors - Elmira, Binghamton and Utica,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fractured in large part by the collapse of the steel industry,
Buffalo's population has fallen to around 300,000 from 358,000 in
1980. Mrs. Clinton also cited a Buffalo News survey that identified
Buffalo residents as ''the most highly taxed citizens in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I'm very optimistic about what can be done but I don't
think we can do what we need to do ... if we deny that we have a
problem,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, visiting a windows manufacturing plant in Johnstown, 38
miles northwest of Albany, said he believed that ''there's much
more work to do'' in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   But ''compared to where the upstate economy was in the late '80s
and early '90s - which were years of high taxes, job loss,
factories moving out of state - I believe that the upstate economy
has turned the corner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, he said, ''would like people to believe that the
upstate economy is some type of vast economic wasteland. I do not
believe that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
