<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill overturning Supreme Court lesbian custody ruling stalls in Assembly </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - State lawmakers Thursday balked at
supporting a bill designed to thwart a New Jersey Supreme Court
decision that deemed a lesbian a legal co-parent to the children of
her ex-partner.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would strip custody or visitation rights from most
people who have no blood or adoption ties to a child.
</P>
<P>
   But the sponsor, Assemblywoman Marion Crecco, R-Essex, held the
bill from consideration when it became apparent that she did not
have sufficient support in the Assembly Senior Issues and Community
Services committee.
</P>
<P>
   The natural mother of the children in the state Supreme Court
case, who goes by the initials M.J.B., testified that her
5-year-old twins suffer psychological problems as a result of
court-ordered visitation with her ex-partner, who is identified in
court documents as V.C.
</P>
<P>
   The justices in April granted V.C. visitation rights, but denied
her custody of the children in a ruling gay activists applauded for
recognizing the ex-partner as a legal co-parent.
</P>
<P>
   M.J.B. has since appealed the case to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Crecco said she introduced the bill to protect children from the
demands of intrusive non-family members who have only fleeting
relationships with the true parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Parental rights are being eroded and it's time it's stopped,''
Crecco said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The potential for a flood of custody and visitation suits from
ex-boyfriends and girlfriends exists and is terribly frightening,''
M.J.B. told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We now need laws to make sure that just living with a kid for
a few months does not entitle an adult to force themselves into
that child's life forever,'' said the mother, an Atlantic County
resident.
</P>
<P>
   She told the committee that police were called to her house
earlier this month to escort her children to V.C.'s for a weekend
visit. The twins, one girl, one boy, were traumatized, she said.
M.J.B.'s new companion took photographs of police entering her
home, copies of which she brought to the committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But committee members said Crecco's bill could backfire by
cutting ties between loving adults and children with whom they
bonded and helped raise.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill would tie the hands of the courts,'' said
Assemblywoman Charlotte Vandervalk, R-Bergen. ''In this day and
age, we have to look at what's best for the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union also opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''The courts have recognized that a child develops a strong bond
with the people who raise him, regardless of their legal status,''
said ACLU staff attorney Leslie Cooper. The courts have set a high
legal standard for people to meet to be awarded parental status,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any fears about nannies, or boyfriends or girlfriends getting
custody is unwarranted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After other committee members also expressed reservations about
the bill, committee Chairman Melvin Cottrell, R-Ocean, warned
Crecco that she lacked the votes to send the bill to the full
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Crecco said she might try again with a different committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, who controls bill committee
assignments, later said there was little chance he would grant
Crecco's wish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
