<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman says no to off-track betting  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A proposal to allow off-track betting was
dealt a serious setback Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman vetoed a bill that would have allowed
racetrack owners, including the state sports authority, to open up
to 15 off-track betting parlors around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have also allowed gamblers to set up accounts at
racetracks so they could bet by phone or over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the measure was the state's own sports authority,
which operates the Meadowlands racetrack and Monmouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters contended off-track betting would boost New Jersey's
flagging horse racing industry.
</P>
<P>
   In her veto message to the Legislature, Whitman said she
supports off-track betting, but wants changes in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's version of the regulations would allow OTB parlors to
operate more efficiently, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed by the Legislature gives 40 percent of the
money bet to purses - or prize money - for owners of winning
horses, with the authority getting 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, who earlier said the purse should be 36 percent, agreed
with the Legislature's higher figure. The current legal split is 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Garland, senior executive vice president of racing for the
New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, said the changes
Whitman wants make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our position is New Jersey needs this legislation. We concur
with the governor. She has crafted an excellent compromise. New
Jersey needs to improve its competitive position. It's time to all
work together to address this issue as well as others that confront
us,'' Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly approved the bill with a 66-13 vote on June 29; the
Senate margin that day was 27-11. Last year, the Senate passed a
version of the bill, but the Assembly did not act on it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought the bill that passed overwhelmingly in both houses
after a great deal of deliberation, not just in the short term, but
it's been out there for two years,'' Assembly Speaker Jack Collins,
R-Salem, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 people work in the horse-racing industry in New
Jersey, and the state needs to protect those interests as well as
agriculture and open-space concerns, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe we need to do something to keep horse racing in the
state of New Jersey, and horse racing to me is not just the two
minutes they run around the track, but also all the extras,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Off-track betting and phone wagering make it easier for people
to bet on horse races. That pumps more money into the industry.
Some of that money goes into making bigger purses, which eventually
attract better horses and more fans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, there were 163 live thoroughbred racing days - 141
fewer than in 1992. With fatter purses and more fans, harness
racing fares better. It had 395 live harness racing days in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1997, annual attendance at New Jersey's tracks
declined from 3.87 million to 2.87 million. The amount wagered also
declined sharply from about $831 million to $467 million, according
to the New Jersey Racing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Racetrack operators would be required to run a minimum number of
live racing days to keep their OTB permits. The bills also require
the state to meet local zoning laws, pay property taxes and obtain
a local liquor license.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, voters approved a referendum that allowed the
state to change the rules governing horse racing. Officials said
the move would preserve horse racing, open space and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But thoroughbred owners faced off against the sports authority,
charging that the original measure was designed to pump money into
the authority, not the horse racing industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
