<HEADLINE> 71-year-old grandmother forges ahead for seat in Congress  </HEADLINE>
By PAT MILTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLPORT, N.Y. (AP) - Reggie Seltzer has been on the go since
squeaking out a victory in a Long Island Democratic primary vote
recount this week. There is no time to waste with only seven weeks
to go until election day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are racing against the clock,'' said Seltzer, her blue
shirt sleeves rolled up to her elbows as she paused to talk in the
backyard of her waterfront home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the underdog,'' she says. ''It's going to be an uphill
fight. But the decks were stacked against me in the primary and we
won.''
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old environmental lawyer was declared the winner by
35 votes on Monday, beating out two-term Congressman Michael Forbes
who had switched from the Republican Party to the Democratic Party
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer now faces Republican Felix Grucci, Supervisor of the
Town of Brookhaven, in November.
</P>
<P>
   Grucci is considered a more formidable opponent than Forbes. He
has a highly recognized name, being a son of the world famous
Grucci fireworks family. He is also expected to spend more than $1
million on the campaign buttressed with funds from the National
Republican Committee who are paying close attention to the Long
Island district.
</P>
<P>
   Registered Republicans in the Suffolk County district outnumber
Democrats by a 2-to1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Grucci is not shifting his campaign strategy for Seltzer, says
Howard Martini, Grucci's senior adviser and former Suffolk GOP
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Felix Grucci is going to campaign on his record,'' says
Martini. ''That doesn't change because there is a different
candidate in the race. The difference between Forbes and Seltzer is
that Forbes abandoned his principles, and Reggie Seltzer has the
wrong principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer points to the environment as one of the most important
issue in the district, and the one in which she and Grucci differ
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Grucci has not met a developer he does not like,'' Seltzer
said. She charged Grucci with turning the district into the
''strip-mall capital of Long Island'' in his role as Brookhaven
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has to be a balance between jobs and the environment,''
Seltzer said. Some of the development decisions under Grucci's
leadership have not only damaged the environment but threaten the
area's tourism-driven economy,'' she argued.
</P>
<P>
   Grucci counters that criticism by saying that he was the driving
force behind the purchase of 500,000 acres of open space in
Brookhaven Township and the passing of a $10 million bond act to
preserve open space and drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer, a self-assured grandmother, says she can't wait to
debate Grucci face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile she continues to run a traditional grass-roots
campaign out of her kitchen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
