<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Reportedly OKs Land Swap  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is willing to
trade land in the West Bank for territory in Israel, a swap aiming
to accommodate Jewish settlers, an American Jewish leader who met
with him said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians are waiting for the United States to
decide whether to offer bridging proposals to break the logjam in
their negotiations, officials from both sides said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are deadlocked over control of holy sites in
Jerusalem, though other key issues, including Palestinian refugees,
Jewish settlements and borders, have not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is committed to reaching an agreement, but ''hasn't
decided on what to sign, when to sign,'' said Abraham Foxman,
national director of the Anti-Defamation League, an American Jewish
group, who met with Arafat late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   New ideas raised by Arafat included solving the plight of
Palestinian refugees in Lebanon first, because unlike in other
countries, refugees in Lebanon are not allowed to work, Foxman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Arafat expressed willingness to grant Israel some
territory in the West Bank claimed by the Palestinians in return
for territory now within the borders of Israel. Some Israeli
officials have put forawrd the swap idea to allow Israel to keep
some of its settlements in the West Bank. Arafat also expressed
willingness to post an international peace force in the Jordan
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told President Clinton in a meeting in New York earlier
this month that the parcels of land traded should be equal in size,
and that the Palestinians would not give up areas above aquifers or
populated regions, according to Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has sent conflicting messages. Acting Foreign Minister
Shlomo Ben-Ami has ruled out land swaps, while Israeli negotiators
said during the Mideast summit at Camp David in July they want to
take 9 percent of the West Bank for 1 percent of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians want a freeze in settlement activity pending an
agreement. On Thursday, an army spokesman confirmed that the
Defense Ministry has approved the 250-acre expansion of the Alfei
Menasheh settlement in the West Bank. Bulldozers have begun
clearing the land in preparation for construction, Capt. Peter
Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Ami said he was worried Americans may not present a summary
document of recent talks if they cannot narrow the wide gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not totally sure that a document will be issued,'' Ben-Ami
told Channel One television. ''If it becomes clear to them that ...
they can't put together a package that can bring the positions of
the two sides together, maybe they won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxman said that in Wednesday's meeting, Arafat tried to show
that the Palestinians are flexible, but that Israel is raising
obstacles. ''It was a whole conversation of things that are
doable,'' Foxman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Arafat showed no willingness to compromise over
Jerusalem, but referred to Jewish feelings for the holy sites
there. Arafat has not acknowledged that the biblical Jewish Temples
stood on the site where an Islamic shrine and mosque are located
now.
</P>
<P>
   The top Palestinian official in east Jerusalem, Faisel Husseini,
warned Thursday that the Palestinians will fight an Israeli plan to
build a superhighway through the disputed sector of the city. City
hall has begun issuing evacuation orders to Palestinians living in
the path of the planned road.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli decision that comes at this time, during
negotiations, shows how much Israel is hesitating in the peace
process,'' Husseini said after a special meeting of a Jerusalem
committee called by Arafat. ''I think that there will be a serious
reaction ... on this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Though no progress has been made toward a peace accord since the
Camp David, Israel and the Palestinians concluded an agreement late
Wednesday on the construction of a seaport in Gaza, after Israeli
security and environmental concerns were cleared up in drawn-out
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had consented to a port in several previous agreements
with the Palestinians, but repeatedly withheld the final go-ahead.
The port is to be ready in 18 months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
