<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill to ban police ticket quotas moves in Assembly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A bill to prevent police departments from
using ticket quotas now goes to the full Assembly for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Law and Public Safety Committee of the lower house
unanimously approved the measure Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ticket quotas are an invitation to overzealousness and
carelessness. They are a cancer that can breed contempt among
police officers and distrust with the general public,'' bill
sponsor Assemblyman Herbert Conaway, D-Burlington, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   A version of the bill passed the Senate 38-0 on June 29. That
measure does not forbid police supervisors from using tickets or
arrest statistics as one way to judge an officer's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Conaway's bill, however, would prevent a police officer's
performance evaluation from being based solely on the number of
tickets written.
</P>
<P>
   The State Policemen's Benevolent Association and the Fraternal
Order of Police, two of the state's biggest police unions, support
his bill, A-2261, Conaway said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Law enforcement officials are not salesmen,'' Conaway said.
''Traffic ticket quotas can divert their attention away from other
more pressing aspects of police work.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Full text of bills available at the Office of
Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
