<HEADLINE> Fashion Week Heads to Finish Line  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCINE PARNES
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With Fashion Week wrapping up, the Halston line
unveiled a slew of shirtdresses and separates in a reminder of why
designer Craig Natiello is acclaimed for his evening wear.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Halston Frowick died in 1990, yet under Natiello the line
still had the late designer's successful signature touches, such as
Ultrasuede. This time, the suede-like fabric was fashioned into
those trendy shirtdresses, as well as cropped jean jackets and
animal-print suits.
</P>
<P>
   Natiello, in his second season running the line, sent out
additional Halstonisms, most notably long and lean slinky gowns
which rise high on the thigh. There were enough gold sequins to
inspire the designer to name a T-shirt dress ''Fort Knox.'' Gold
lace blanketed everything from turtlenecks to wrap dresses -- and
there were splashes of sequins.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really the snottiness of taking a shirtdress and beading
it,'' said Natiello, who has dressed Sharon Stone and Geena Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In its first Fashion Week show since Bill Blass stepped down
from the helm, his namesake design house introduced a new head
designer and a new look.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Slowick stayed true in part to the Blass course, sending
out familiar signatures, most notably menswear fabrics like
pinstripes and houndstooth, and tweed splattered with sequins.
</P>
<P>
   ''First, I talked with Mr. Blass and literally interviewed him,
and we discussed the spirit of Bill Blass,'' Slowick said after the
show. ''I wanted to integrate that with my own touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Geoffrey Beene offered a still-life presentation of
his spring line on mannequins.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is full of perennial Beene favorites, which
illustrate his unusual use of color and cut. A two-toned gown is
solid black on one side, and striped in black and white on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   The line also showcases Beene trademarks such as black jersey
gowns with cutouts, and cropped, simple boleros. Beene also
reprised his imaginative gloves, this time in polka dots and
fanciful colors.
</P>
<P>
   New York designer Anna Sui packed the house Wednesday night with
a lineup of '80s punk-inspired black dresses slashed to pieces and
accessorized with fishnet hosiery and mile-high spike heels.
Fingerless gloves suggested Madonna in her earlier days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sui nodded to trends of the moment, offering safari
jackets, pleated skirts and off-the shoulder dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Week wraps up Friday with Donna Karan and Calvin Klein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
