<HEADLINE> Ross indicted in 1982 murder in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLETOWN, N.Y. (AP) - Serial killer Michael Ross, on death row
for the murders of four teen-age girls in Connecticut in the early
1980s, has been indicted in an 18-year-old murder in New York.
</P>
<P>
   DNA evidence links Ross to the rape and murder of Paula Perrara,
a high school student who disappeared from Wallkill, N.Y. in March,
1982, prosecutors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Michael Ross picked her up, drove her to a secluded area,
dragged her from his car, raped her and murdered her,'' said Frank
Phillips, the district attorney for Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was a student at Cornell University at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Police in New York linked Ross to the case after he admitted in
a BBC interview that he had committed at least one murder in New
York that had not been linked to him. New York police got a search
warrant and collected DNA samples from Ross - which matched those
found on Perrara.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has previously confessed to two other murders in New York,
but has never been tried in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Ross was resentenced to death in the murders of four
Connecticut women. Ross admitted preying on his victims as they
walked or hitchhiked down quiet country roads in New London County.
He raped some of them. Ross also is serving two life sentences for
killing two other women in Windham County.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, 40, was convicted of the slayings and sentenced to death
in 1987, but the state Supreme Court in 1994 overturned the
penalty. The high court ruled that information was withheld from
the defense that might have helped Ross get life in prison and
ordered a new penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   During that hearing, Ross claimed a disorder called sexual
sadism drove him to rape and kill - a defense the jury rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
