<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Seen Lacking Staff for Probes  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government agency that investigates
anticompetitive behavior in cattle and hog markets lacks the
training and legal expertise to do the job, congressional auditors
say.
</P>
<P>
   The Grain Inspection, Packers and Stockyards Administration,
part of the Agriculture Department, is ''better positioned for
performing economic analyses'' than for developing cases to prove
that ''anticompetitive practices have occurred,'' according to a
report by the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   USDA could learn from the agencies that enforce antitrust laws
in other areas of the economy -- the Justice Department and the
Federal Trade Commission -- and use teams of attorneys and
economists to conduct investigations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO is the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department has come under criticism from farmers
and ranchers who don't think the agency has done enough to curb the
power of large meatpackers.
</P>
<P>
   The department ''has been ineffective at addressing growing
concerns about competition in the livestock market and because of
the agency's shortcoming, potential violations may not have been
pursued,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa. USDA hasn't used the
money Congress has given it effectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The packers and stockyards administration relies on its staff of
18 economists to investigate complaints about cattle and hog
markets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's general counsel assigns some of its lawyers to
help investigate the cases, but the number of attorneys has been
cut from eight to five because of budget constraints.
</P>
<P>
   From Oct. 1, 1997, through the end of 1999, the department
opened 74 investigations involving cattle or hog markets. As of
March 57 had been completed, and violations were found in five of
those, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   USDA ''will be looking very seriously'' at the report's
recommendations, said Susan McAvoy, a spokeswoman for Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are aggressively working to ensure fair competition in the
industry,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Meat Institute, which represents major meatpackers,
issued a statement saying that the industry ''supports continuous
education'' within USDA ''to understand our industry's rapidly
evolving business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gao.gov
</P>
<P>
   GIPSA: http://www.usda.gov/gipsa
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 1921 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0179 </DOCNO>
