<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki says he is opposed to a Yankees move to Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Gov. George Pataki said Thursday that he will
not back a move by the Yankees to Manhattan's west side, and said
any move to the city by the Jets would have to be beneficial to the
public and not just to private interests.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several days, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has spoken
about the need for a stadium with a retractible roof on Manhattan
property owned by the state's Metropolitan Transportation Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the facility could be used by the Jets or Yankees,
as well as for conventions and the 2012 Olympics, which the city is
pushing for. In recent days, the mayor has met with officials from
the Jets about the stadium proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium would likely not be built without the governor's
support.
</P>
<P>
   While Pataki said Thursday that he was open-minded about the $1
billion stadium, he ruled out a move by the Yankees and threw cold
water on a Jets move.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me make it plain, if the idea is to move the Yankees from
the Bronx, I will oppose it strenuously,'' Pataki said at a
Manhattan news conference. ''It cannot be any part of this
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium has aroused significant opposition from the area's
political leaders due to concerns about noise and traffic. Pataki
said during a call-in show on WCBS radio that the stadium ''has to
be in the public interest...Not just in the private interest.''
</P>
<P>
   One alternative, Pataki said, is to build a stadium for the Jets
near Shea Stadium in Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
