<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes home improvement registration bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Legislation backed by Gov. Christie Whitman
that would force home improvement contractors to register with the
state passed the Senate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, S-831, passed 29-7 and now heads to the Assembly for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would require all home improvement contractors to
register with the state or county in which they work.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would also establish fines to punish unscrupulous
contractors who commit consumer fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Violators would be subject to fines up to $7,500 for a first
offense, and $15,000 for second or subsequent offenses, under the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said in a statement after the Senate vote that the bill
will provide much-needed protections for New Jersey residents,
especially vulnerable senior citizens, who hire home improvement
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, more than 50,000 state residents report they've been
the victim of a home repair rip-off, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Without the law, ''Essentially, anyone with a business card,
truck and tools can claim to be a home improvement contractor,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, the threat of prosecution is not enough to deter
these bad apples, and we must now go a step further,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
