<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Halston, Blass, Beene and Sui move towards the Fashion Week finish line </HEADLINE>
by 
o0224nyc--
r n BC-NY--FashionWeek 1stLd-Writethru 500 09-21 0505
BC-NY--Fashion Week, 1st Ld-Writethru, 500   
Halston, Blass, Beene and Sui move towards the Fashion Week finish
line   
Eds: SUBS lead to include time reference.
AP Photos
By Francine Parnes
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - As Fashion Week headed towards the home stretch
Thursday, the Halston line returned for its second season under
designer Craig Natiello, with a slew of shirtdresses and separates,
reminding the audience why Halston was acclaimed for his evening
wear in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Halston Frowick died in 1990, yet under Natiello, the line
continues with the late designer's successful signature touches,
such as Ultrasuede. This time the suede-like fabric was fashioned
into trendy shirtdresses, cropped jean jackets and animal-print
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Natiello sent out additional Halstonisms, most notably long and
lean slinky gowns which rise high on the thigh. There were enough
gold sequins to inspire the designer to name a T-shirt dress ''Fort
Knox.'' Gold lace blanketed everything from turtlenecks to wrap
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Natiello advanced the Halston idea of casual looks, dressed up
for evening, such as shirtdresses, splashed all over with sequins.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really the snottiness of taking a shirtdress and beading
it,'' said Natiello, who has dressed Sharon Stone and Geena Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In its first Fashion Week show since Bill Blass stepped down
from the helm, his namesake design house introduced a new head
designer and a new look.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Slowick stayed true in part to the Blass course, sending
out familiar signatures, most notably menswear fabrics like
pinstripes and houndstooth, and tweed splattered with sequins.
Still, the Slowick spin was evident throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ''First I talked with Mr. Blass and literally interviewed him,
and we discussed the spirit of Bill Blass,'' said Slowick, behind
the curtain in the post-show crunch. ''I wanted to integrate that
with my own touch.''
</P>
<P>
   His challenge will be to keep the Blass loyals while attracting
a wider customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the Fashion Week circuit, Geoffrey Beene offered a
still-life presentation of his spring line on mannequins.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is full of perennial Beene favorites, which
illustrate his unusual use of color and cut. A two-toned gown is
solid black on one side, and striped in black and white on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   The line also showcases Beene trademarks such as black jersey
gowns with cutouts, and cropped, simple boleros. Beene also
reprised his imaginative gloves, this time in polka dots and
fanciful colors.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night starred Anna Sui, the New York designer who
packed the house with a crush of young faces, there to glimpse her
lineup of '80s punk-inspired black dresses slashed to pieces and
accessorized with fishnet hosiery and mile-high spike heels.
Fingerless gloves suggested Madonna in her earlier days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sui nodded to trends of the moment such as safari
jackets, pleated skirts and off-the shoulder dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Week wraps up Friday with Donna Karan and Calvin Klein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
