<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine claims donation to black minister preceded his candidacy  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine
told a college audience on Thursday that his $25,000 donation to an
influential minister's church was made by his family foundation
before he was a candidate for office.
</P>
<P>
   However, documents provided by Corzine himself this week show
the check from the Jon and Joanne Corzine Foundation to St.
Matthew's AME Church of Orange was written on December 9, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine left the Goldman Sachs investment firm in May 1999 and
by the next month had made public his interest in seeking federal
office, spending his own money on consultants and forming a
political committee to transmit those funds.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor of St. Matthews is the Rev. Reginald Jackson,
executive director of the Black Ministers Council, which has played
a prominent role in recent years on minority and State Police
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although the church council does not usually back political
candidates, its officers, including Jackson, gave Corzine a crucial
endorsement last April in his successful quest to defeat former
Gov. Jim Florio in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the remark after the Thursday night program that was
taped to be aired on the News 12 cable TV station Wednesday,
Corzine stuck by it and denied it was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   He told a small group of reporters outside the Rutgers
University hall and away from the TV cameras that while the check
was dated in December, it had been promised in July.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he was not yet a candidate that July, but was only
exploring the idea before making the announcement official in
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded his own tax records dated the check to December,
Corzine said, ''Right. I pledged it to them before I was a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I pledged it to them in the summer. I pledged it to them in
July,'' Corzine said. ''I wasn't a candidate until September.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said his decision to form committees, hire consultants
and spend funds starting in June did not count as a candidacy. ''It
was in the exploratory phase, because we were actually working to
find out whether we were going to run or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine on Thursday continued to denounce claims by Republican
opponent Bob Franks that the donations of the private foundation
were designed for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine became agitated as news reporters pressed him on the
point, walking away from their questions to get into a car that
whisked him off to what spokesman Tom Shea described as a private
meeting with Florio and some of his aides from the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it is outside the context of anything I've given
to a lot of other churches,'' Corzine said. ''I don't think anyone
is claiming I was trying to influence the Catholic Church,'' to
which his foundation gave $200,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine also told the college audience Thursday he believed it
was proper to keep silent about his foundation gift when the
officers of the Black Ministers Council held a news conference in
April to offer him their personal endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   At the April news conference, another council officer said there
had been no donation from Corzine. Corzine did not speak up to
correct him at the time. He said Thursday he did not because the
question was not directed at him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like that discussion that was taking place, was
directed toward them, I let them answer the question,'' he said.
''I think it was the responsibility of the Rev. Jackson to deal
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The question was was Jon Corzine trying to buy political
favors, and he wasn't. Period,'' Corzine said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 2023 </TRAILER>
