<DOCNO> APW20000921.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Whitman makes changes to charter school measure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Thursday returned
to the Legislature a bill designed to fix inequities in the way
charter schools are funded.
</P>
<P>
   Although she did not touch the funding revisions, Whitman did
suggest three other changes to the bill, A-1344, that require
additional legislative action for the entire bill to become law.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would provide about $10 million more in aid to fund
charter schools to address recent rulings by an independent state
panel that overturned the state's original funding formulas.
</P>
<P>
   One ruling struck down state regulations that said local
districts must give charter schools 90 percent of what they
actually spend on education. Instead, the ruling said the districts
only had to pay the charters 90 percent of what the state deems
sufficient for a ''thorough and efficient'' education, which is
generally less than actual costs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was about a $6 million loss to charter schools,
with the state paying the freight, under the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The second fix would funnel $3.8 million in state funds through
districts to charter schools for students who transfer from private
and parochial schools, another district or a home-schooled setting
into charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   This way, the local district does not have to pay the charter
school for a pupil it never enrolled in the first place, and
therefore never received state aid for.
</P>
<P>
   These funding provisions remain intact under Whitman's
conditional veto of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor suggested lawmakers slow down a review of the
experimental schools. The bill called for a report on the schools'
progress by February 2001; Whitman recommended postponing that to
October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   She also opposed a bill provision making permanent enrollment
caps on charter schools, at least until after the results of the
overall review are complete.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Whitman suggested a new bill provision. She wants to
direct the schools to provide the state with the names and
addresses of all students and staff of all the schools in case they
need to be notified of any change in a school's status.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the state revoked the charters of two schools, one
each in Essex and Atlantic counties, due to financial
mismanagement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-21-00 2034 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000921.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kills 64 in India  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Torrential rain and floods in India's
eastern West Bengal state killed at least 64 people and left some
10 million people marooned Thursday as the army struggled to carry
out rescue and relief operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is very grim. Only the military can help us
out,'' the United News of India quoted West Bengal chief minister
Jyoti Basu as saying in Calcutta, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said 26 people were killed in the worst-affected
district of Birbhum.
</P>
<P>
   Indian air force helicopters were dropping food packets in the
affected areas, home to millions, United News reported. Press Trust
of India said many people were stranded on rooftops and dependent
on airlifts for food and water.
</P>
<P>
   Army boats were ferrying people to safer places and carrying
food, medicines and water supplies to inaccessible areas.
</P>
<P>
   The rain has caused extensive flooding, ravaged crops and washed
out houses and grain-filled warehouses. Authorities also discharged
excess water from two reservoirs in the region, increasing flood
levels, United News of India said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Congress party members met Deputy Chief Minister
Buddhadeb Bhattacharya to complain that sufficient aid was not
reaching people in five districts, Press Trust reported.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Bangladesh, about a dozen people were killed and
35 injured as tornadoes and heavy rains lashed the country,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
