<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Jewish Leader Is Concerned  </HEADLINE>
By COLLEEN BARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The leader of Germany's Jewish community expressed
fears Thursday that a postwar taboo on expressing anti-Semitic
views is breaking down -- and not just in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to government leaders and foreign dignitaries, Paul
Spiegel honored Germany's postwar democracy during celebrations
marking the 50th anniversary of the Central Council of Jews in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Spiegel's remarks revealed a pessimism that went deeper than
concerns expressed following a string of right-wing attacks on
foreigners this summer, including a still-unsolved bombing attack
at a Duesseldorf train station that injured 10 recent immigrants
from the Soviet Union, six of them Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel said that anti-Semitism in Germany has decreased
slightly since 1974 when experts established that 20 percent of the
population exhibited ''manifest anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What has changed, however, is the openness with which
anti-Semitism is now expressed,'' Spiegel said. ''Many anti-Semites
found it inopportune to express their anti-Semitism 10 years ago.
Today, they express it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said anti-Semitic views have become increasingly common among
the political, industrial and cultural elite since German writer
Martin Walser's 1998 speech expressing frustration that images of
the Holocaust were used against Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel emphasized that anti-foreigner hate, at the root of the
attacks in Germany this summer, is not just a German phenomenon. He
specifically cited Austria, and criticized European Union leaders'
decision to end sanctions imposed after the far-right Freedom Party
joined government.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegel also said the Roman Catholic Church, despite
considerable efforts to improve ties with Jews, is not completely
immune from anti-Semitic thinking.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a recent magazine interview with Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger, the powerful Vatican official who oversees Roman
Catholic doctrine, expressing what he said was the Catholic
church's hope that Jews will one day embrace Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ''And we have not heard a final answer why the convinced
anti-Semite Pope Pius IX was recently beatified,'' Spiegel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Council of Jews in Germany was founded on July 19,
1950, by Holocaust survivors who chose to remain in the country
that intended their destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's prewar population of 600,000 was the most assimilated
in Europe, Spiegel said, adding: ''Jews' love of Germany proved
itself over time to be one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 400,000 German Jews escaped the Nazis by emigrating. Of the
remaining 200,000, only 12,000 survived the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish population in Germany was 15,000 by the early 1950s
when the council was founded. By 1989 the population had doubled to
30,000. But since the collapse of communism, Germany's Jewish
population has surged to 85,000 with immigrants from the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent violence, the new arrivals want to stay in
Germany, Spiegel said, which is evident by their queries how to
obtain German citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder honored the council
for its role in creating a strong postwar democracy and launching a
campaign against right-wing extremism.
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasized Germany's ongoing responsibility to educate
its citizens about the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   He said memorials should also remember those who resisted the
Nazis, not to diminish German responsibility, but to disprove the
notion that ''We couldn't do anything'' or ''We didn't know
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 2052 </TRAILER>
