<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Federal Liberals Feel Pressure To Reduce Fuel Prices
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The federal government, under mounting pressure to
help consumers cope with rising gasoline and home heating bills, is
considering unilateral action if it can't get provincial agreement
on a joint strategy to knock down prices.
</P>
<P>
   Knocking a few cents off federal fuel taxes -- an approach urged
by the Canadian Alliance and Conservatives -- is one option under
study.
</P>
<P>
   But sources say the Liberal government is also considering a
variety of rebate schemes that would ensure the cash goes directly
to taxpayers and doesn't end up padding the profits of the energy
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Paul Martin, who has repeatedly stated he wants
a federal-provincial deal before taking action, continued to insist
publicly Thursday that is his preferred choice.
</P>
<P>
   Joint action is the best way to ensure retail prices drop enough
to make a difference to consumers, Martin suggested outside the
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is to be a reduction in excise taxes . . . clearly it
would have to have sufficient impact so that it would not simply
disappear into the pockets of the oil companies, that it would
benefit Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, government strategists acknowledged
they were feeling the political heat and appeared resigned to
moving on their own if the provinces won't come onside.
Quebec Panel Rules On Trademarks
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Second Cup cafes in Quebec can continue selling
coffee and biscotti under the chain's English-language banner.
</P>
<P>
   The English signs advertising Home Depot, Future Shop and Burger
King, among others, also can stay. A provincial advisory body has
decided chains with trademark names don't have to adopt French
monikers to comply with Quebec's language laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Conseil de la langue francaise concluded there is nothing it
can do about the fact Quebec's French language charter doesn't
apply to signs that are also legal trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   The charter requires that French be predominant on commercial
signs.
</P>
<P>
   The Conseil recommended that Quebec offer incentives to get
chains to voluntarily adopt French names.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Lucien Bouchard suggested Thursday there is little else
the provincial government can do.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we can legislate to say to an organization: From
now on in Quebec, you will use a name different from the one you
have used throughout your existence and throughout the world,''
Bouchard said Thursday in Baie-Comeau, Quebec
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard's comments came after Quebec's deputy premier warned
the province could end up trying to legislate the changes.
Supreme Court Dismisses Bernardo Appeal Application
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Paul Bernardo, one of the country's most reviled
criminals, appears to have exhausted his last appeal effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Supreme Court of Canada dismissed Bernardo's
application to appeal his first-degree murder conviction without
providing reasons, as is usual.
</P>
<P>
   Bernardo was convicted in 1995 for raping, torturing and killing
Leslie Mahaffy, 14, and Kristen French, 15, in the St. Catharines,
Ontario, suburb of Port Dalhousie.
</P>
<P>
   Bernardo's lawyer, Tony Bryant, said the dismissal seems to end
his client's legal recourse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that it exhausts all options,'' he said from
Toronto. ''If he knows of another appeal, it would be news to me.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that all of the families, including Mr. Bernardo's
parents, . . . the French and Mahaffy families and the Homolka
family, can finally get on with the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Danson, lawyer for the Mahaffy and French families, said the
decision offers ''substantial closure'' as they rebuild shattered
lives without their daughters.
Ottawa Sets Deadline To End Fishing Dispute
</P>
<P>
   BURNT CHURCH, New Brunswick (AP) -- The federal government has
run out of patience with native lobster fishermen in New Brunswick
and seemed prepared Thursday to bring an abrupt end to the bitter,
potentially explosive standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The Fisheries and Oceans Department gave defiant Mi'kmaq
fishermen from the Burnt Church reserve a deadline of 11 a.m.
Friday to pull their traps out of Miramichi Bay or face
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimatum was in a letter sent by the Fisheries Department
to Chief Wilbur Dedam and the band council at the Burnt Church
reserve informing them the fishery is closed and all traps must be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   While there was no immediate response from the band council, the
mood on the Mi'kmaq reserve in the province's northeast corner was
grim and determined.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be a good day to die,'' said Frank Thomas, war chief
of the Mi'kmaq warrior society, when asked what he thought will
happen when the deadline passes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is from the Indian Brook First Nation in Shubenacadie,
Nova Scotia, which lost a critical court decision Thursday that
would have kept Fisheries Department officers from seizing lobster
traps and other native gear.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Court of Canada denied an injunction sought by
Indian Brook challenging the federal government's jurisdiction in
regulating the disputed Maritime lobster fishery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
