<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Considers Fund for Rebels  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's government said Thursday it
might consider creating a fund for leftist rebels if they stopped
kidnapping people for ransom and agreed to a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by presidential peace envoy Camilo Gomez followed
the guerrillas' abduction last weekend of as many as 80 people from
a highway outside Cali, the country's third-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Roman Catholic Bishop Jaime Prieto of the
eastern city of Barrancabermeja urged such a fund be created, to
feed and clothe the estimated 20,000 fighters in Colombia's two
rebel armies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters whether the government agreed with Prieto,
Gomez said he was not ruling out the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are willing to analyze, under the appropriate conditions,
any alternatives. One of the alternatives could be just that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's second-largest insurgency, the National Liberation
Army, is still holding as many as 37 of the people they abducted in
daylight raids Sunday on restaurants and an estate outside the
western city of Cali.
</P>
<P>
   The group is presumed to be seeking ransoms as well as political
concessions from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's biggest rebel group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia, also relies on kidnapping -- as well as narcotics
production -- to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much Colombia needs a solution to its protracted civil
war was demonstrated Thursday, when the city of Bogota canceled the
sale of its phone company, blaming guerrilla violence for scaring
off foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Mayor Enrique Penalosa was expected to drive
the Colombian currency downward. Officials had hoped to raise at
least $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Penalosa said escalating violence was to blame for the aborted
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies who had been expected to bid for the phone
company, known as ETB, were Spain's Telefonica and Italy's Telecom
Italia. Both pulled out, Penalosa said.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment in Colombia has withered amid an upsurge in
fighting in the South American country's decades-old armed conflict
during the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrillas have kidnapped foreign executives and regularly
extort private companies as well as bombing oil pipelines and
electrical pylons. The rebels oppose the sale of state-run
industries to international companies, considering it a sellout to
foreign interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
