<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tropical Storm Heads to Gulf Coast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- Storm warnings were posted along the Gulf Coast today
after Tropical Storm Helene formed and quickly gained strength in the Gulf of
Mexico. The center of the storm was expected to make landfall sometime tomorrow
near Fort Walton Beach, east of Pensacola. A hurricane watch was posted for much
of the western Florida coast and at least 5 to 8 inches of rain were expected in
many areas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Bring Tech To Disabled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- President Clinton got a close-up demonstration today of
technology that's helping people with disabilities connect to cyberspace.
Clinton toured a center that trains people with disabilities to use new tools to
access the Internet. He also was to speak to about 800 people at a reception
that will raise an estimated $350,000 for the Democratic Party in Michigan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bush Battle Over Oil Reserve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Md. (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore today proposed tapping the nation's
emergency oil reserve to force down gasoline and heating oil prices, as both
cold weather and the election draw closer. Republican rival George W. Bush said
the vice president was risking national security for ''short-term political
gain.'' With half-full heating oil tanks in the background at a Maryland oil
distributorship, Gore said he had urged President Clinton to approve ''several''
releases of 5 million barrels of oil from the government's stockpile to ease
tight supplies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accuser Sues Clinton, First Lady
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kathleen Willey sued President Clinton, his wife and his
lawyers today, alleging they illegally released personal letters Willey sent the
president. The lawsuit filed in federal court alleges invasion of privacy and
recounts the White House's decision to publicize Willey's friendly
correspondence with Clinton. The release was designed to undermine her story
that she was the victim of an unwelcome sexual advance by the president in 1993.
Willey wrote the letters after the alleged advance. The White House released the
letters in 1998 during the Monica Lewinsky scandal after Willey spoke out on
national television.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Firestone: Ford Had Wrong Pressure
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The tire pressure that Ford recommends for Explorers is
lower than what Bridgestone/Firestone suggests and makes the popular sport
utility vehicle less safe, a tire company executive told Congress Thursday. The
tire maker wrote Ford this week requesting it raise the recommended pressure
from 26 pounds per square inch (psi) to 30 pounds, Bridgestone/Firestone
executive vice president John Lampe told a House Commerce subcommittee.
Firestone tires, which have been linked to 101 U.S. traffic deaths, are standard
equipment on the Explorer, the world's best-selling sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescued Cubans Await Word From INS
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Six of the nine Cubans rescued after their stolen
crop-duster crashed at sea were taken to Miami today for interviews with
immigration officials. The others -- a married couple hospitalized with injuries
from the crash and their 6-year-old son -- remained in Key West. Cuba, which had
called the incident a hijacking, now says it was an act of piracy that will
complicate previously planned migration talks beginning today between Cuba and
the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Intel Warns On 3Q Expectations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Stung by weakened demand in Europe, Intel today warned
that its third-quarter revenues will be significantly below Wall Street's
expectations. The news sent shares of Intel down $11.67, or nearly 19 percent,
to $49.81, after finishing the regular trading session on the Nasdaq Stock
Market at $61.48, down $1.58. The Santa Clara-based chip maker said its revenue
for the period ending Sept. 30 will range between $8.5 billion and $8.7 billion,
about 3 percent to 5 percent higher than second-quarter revenue of $8.3 billion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 78; Nasdaq Falls 68
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mixed today amid lingering gloom on Wall
Street about corporate profits and higher oil prices. The uncertainty ended a
two-day rally in the high-tech sector. The Dow Jones industrial average closed
up 77.60 at 10,765.52, according the preliminary calculations. Decliners led
advancers by a 8-to-5 margin on the NYSE. The Nasdaq composite index fell 68.57
to 3,828.87.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astros Beat Cardinals 7-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A day after St. Louis clinched the NL Central, Houston
rookie Tony McKnight allowed two earned runs in 6 2-3 innings to lead the Astros
over the Cardinals 7-5 today. Cards manager Tony La Russa didn't start Jim
Edmonds and three other regulars.
AP NewsBrief By HOWARD SINER 
</P>
