<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accuser Sues Clinton, First Lady  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Presidential accuser Kathleen Willey Schwicker
sued President Clinton, his wife and his lawyers Thursday, alleging
they illegally released personal letters the former White House
volunteer sent the president.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was assigned to U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth,
a Reagan appointee who concluded earlier this year that Clinton
committed a criminal violation of the Privacy Act by releasing the
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Schwicker's lawsuit alleges invasion of privacy and recounts the
White House's decision to publicize her friendly correspondence
with Clinton. The release was designed to undermine her story that
she was the victim of an unwelcome sexual advance by the president
in 1993. Schwicker wrote the letters after the alleged advance. The
White House released the letters in 1998 during the Monica Lewinsky
scandal after Schwicker detailed the alleged sexual advance on
national television.
</P>
<P>
   Schwicker also alleges the White House was behind the release of
confidential information about the failure to repay $200,000 that
her husband at the time, a lawyer, took from a client's escrow
account. She signed a contract agreeing to repay the money, but
never did so. Amid mounting debts, her husband committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' personal lawyer, David Kendall, who was among
those sued by Schwicker, declined to comment about the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The case was assigned to Lamberth because he is handling a
related lawsuit filed by Judicial Watch, the same conservative
group representing Schwicker. The other lawsuit was filed by former
White House employees of Republican presidencies whose FBI
background files were gathered by the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly Kathleen Willey, she changed her name after her
marriage to longtime friend Bill Schwicker last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 2121 </TRAILER>
