<DOCNO> APW20000921.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamond Group Wants Certifying Plan  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNA LOOF
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) -- Representatives of the world's
leading diamond exporting, processing and importing countries
agreed Thursday to develop a plan to keep diamonds mined by rebel
groups off the international market.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, all diamonds sold on the world market would have
to be accompanied by a certificate confirming their origins.
</P>
<P>
   The plan aims to prevent so-called ''blood diamonds'' -- gems
sold by rebels to finance conflicts -- from entering the legitimate
market. Diamonds have helped finance the conflicts in Sierra Leone,
Angola and the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The agreement we have decided upon today is actually a
lifeline out of a situation in which people could feel that they
were unable to distinguish between diamonds from conflicts such as
Sierra Leone and Angola and diamonds legitimately mined,'' said
Peter Hain, Britain's foreign minister for Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came at the end of a three-day conference on
ending the trade in conflict diamonds that was attended by
ministers and representatives from 20 countries, including the
United States, Russia, Canada and Great Britain. The officials
agreed to co-sponsor a resolution to be presented to the U.N.
General Assembly before December and said they hoped a world treaty
could be created next year.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on the rebels' share of the $6 billion-a-year
international diamond trade range from 4 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the conference emphasized, however, that
diamonds were also vital resources for stable countries such as
Namibia and Botswana, and the diamond industry employed tens of
thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   The work to halt the illicit diamond trade would not wait for
the ratification of a treaty, Hain said. Diamond industry
representatives and nations involved in the diamond trade would
begin working to stop the sale of conflict diamonds as soon as
possible, Hain said.
</P>
<P>
   The work was necessary, not only to stop the flow of money to
rebel groups, but also to restore consumer confidence in the gems
and ensure the survival of the diamond industry, Hain said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations already has banned the purchase of diamonds
from rebels in Angola and Sierra Leone. There is no ban affecting
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The certification scheme would largely be financed by countries
involved in the trade, said Phunzile Mlambo-Ngucke, South Africa's
minister for minerals and energy. Conference participants hoped the
United Nations would contribute money, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 2122 </TRAILER>
