<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Edward O. Miller
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTINE, Maine (AP) -- The Rev. Edward O. Miller, an Episcopal
minister known for backing liberal causes, died Sept. 16 following
a long illness. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken liberal minister was best known for testifying
before the House Judiciary Committee in 1964 against a
constitutional amendment to allow prayer in public school.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke on behalf of the American Civil Liberties Union. He was
a member of the ACLU's board.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came to Castine after retiring from St. George's
Episcopal Church in New York, where he served as rector from 1946
to 1975. He also was a member of the board of the Union Theological
Seminary in New York.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Louis Sieff
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French photographer Jean-Louis Sieff, best known
for highly sensual fashion shots in black and white, died
Wednesday. Sieff was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Sieff was born on Nov. 30, 1933 to Polish immigrants. A graduate
of the National Photo-Cinema School in Paris, he went on to become
famous for his black-and-white nudes.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the Magnum photo agency, Elle Magazine, Vogue,
Harper's Bazaar, Photo Revue and Paris-Match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
