<DOCNO> APW20000921.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Hits Ohio Town and Kills 1  </HEADLINE>
By KATE ROBERTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   XENIA, Ohio (AP) -- Randi Helton heard only sirens from
ambulances.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ''I opened the back door to look for the dog and heard the
most awful roar you ever heard,'' he said in describing the
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   He and other residents of this southwest Ohio city, where a
twister 26 years ago caused millions in damage, didn't get much
warning Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado killed one man, injured at least 115 other people,
flattened buildings, uprooted trees and tossed vehicles. Two other
tornadoes swept through five counties in northeast and central Ohio
Wednesday night, the National Weather Service confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Leonard, assistant city manager, said he was paged by
the city's emergency dispatch center at 7:28 p.m. Wednesday. The
center was alerted by two residents who called after seeing the
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said that only one of the five warning sirens in the
city went off.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the time we got the call, power was out in that part of
town,'' Leonard said. The sirens do not have backup batteries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's tornado, Leonard said, followed a path parallel to
the April 3, 1974, tornado that killed 33 people.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Parker, a meteorologist with the National Weather
Service, said the latest storm developed too quickly and moved too
fast to issue a tornado warning.
</P>
<P>
   ''This storm didn't exhibit the classic signature on radar that
indicates a tornado,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Large tornadoes such as the one that struck Xenia Wednesday are
usually easier to track, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft, who declared an emergency in Xenia, a city of
about 24,660 people about 20 miles from Dayton, toured the damage
Thursday morning. The designation allows the city to apply for
disaster relief money. Also, about 45 Ohio Army National Guard
soldiers have been mobilized to assist with traffic control and
security.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Van Pelt, who described his home as flattened, spent
Thursday retrieving what he could and loading it into his
brother-in-law's pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe we had two tornadoes in this town,'' he said
referring to the 1974 tornado. ''I am starting to think Mother
Nature is out to teach a lesson to the people of Xenia.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
</P>
<P>
   City of Xenia: www.ci.xenia.oh.us/
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Emergency Management Agency:
http://www.state.oh.us/odps/division/ema/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
