<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers join fight to stop new sex offender prison  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A ranking Republican lawmaker petitioned
Gov. Christie Whitman for help Thursday to block the construction
of a 300-bed prison for sex offenders in Cumberland County.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier plans put the prison in Woodbridge Township, but that
prompted organized opposition and lawsuits from Middlesex County
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders in Maurice River Township initially praised the
plan to put the facility in the state's far southwest corner. The
town's deputy mayor even called it a ''win-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before residents balked.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, now says residents
should not have to put up with another state prison in their town.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the government of Maurice River Township made the
initial request to be considered as a site, they have since
rescinded their request,'' Collins said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The citizens of our region, and almost every elected official,
agree with the Maurice Township government's decision,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly speaker cited a Superior Court decision that he
said ''removed any legal impediments to the state's siting
procedures'' as one reason Whitman could agree with his request.
</P>
<P>
   A message left Thursday night for Whitman's spokesman was not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he understood the state has a difficult task in
finding a permanent home for the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, the residents of Cumberland County have done more
than their fair share in responding to the state's correctional
needs. They should not be asked to do any more,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials had agreed to pay Maurice River $200,000 a
year while the prison is being built and $825,000 once it begins to
operate.
</P>
<P>
   The state originally planned to build the facility in the Avenel
section of Woodbridge, on the grounds of East Jersey State Prison
and next to the 30-year-old Adult Diagnostic and Treatment Center,
which houses sex offenders during their prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   But residents objected, and Woodbridge challenged the decision
in court.
</P>
<P>
   The state will continue to house 100 sex offenders at East
Jersey until the $20 million facility opens. A Corrections
Department spokesman said earlier that a ''conservative''
completion date is at least two years away.
</P>
<P>
   The state plans to build the prison and is still considering
Woodbridge or Maurice River, corrections spokesman Chris Carden
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Woodbridge was not taken off the table,'' Carden said.
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge ruled Wednesday the state could continue
to build a temporary prison at Avenel while it searched for the
permanent location, Carden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Maurice River proposal was to put the new prison on the
grounds of Bayside State Prison.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bayside, a medium-security facility housing
almost 2,400 inmates, Maurice River Township is the site of
Southern State Correctional Facility, a medium-security prison with
about 1,650 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The new prison will house ''civilly committed'' sex offenders -
those considered dangerous even after their prison terms on
criminal charges end. It will employ about 100 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
