<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Term Limits Proposed in Nebraska  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN O'HANLON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- When the dust settled from the whirlwind
1990s term limits movement, voters or legislatures in 18 states had
set caps on how long state lawmakers could serve in office.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Nebraska. Voters approved term limits measures of
one sort or another three times during the decade but were thwarted
in the courts each time.
</P>
<P>
   The setbacks have not discouraged Guy Curtis, a lawyer in the
town of Imperial who pushed to return term limits to the statewide
ballot Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   In Nebraska -- one of 21 states where individuals can create laws
by putting issues to a popular vote -- people will be asked once
again to limit state lawmakers to two consecutive, four-year terms
in their nonpartisan, single-chamber Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been trying to get legislators to enact term limits for
years,'' said Curtis, who leads the Nebraska Term Limits Committee.
''But a hog won't butcher itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is the only state with a statewide ballot measure that
would impose term limits.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, voters will decide on a constitutional amendment
that would remove term limits for elected county offices. County
officials have been subject to term limits since 1914. Currently,
they may serve two consecutive four-year terms, then must wait two
years before they are eligible to run for any county office.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide a decade ago, an unhappy electorate latched onto term
limits. Oklahoma, Colorado and California paved the way in 1990 and
others followed
</P>
<P>
   A Omaha World-Herald poll published Friday shows 56 percent of
those asked favored limiting state lawmakers to two consecutive
terms. In past elections, voters overwhelmingly supported such
measures by an average of 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, most state lawmakers are against the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an artificial limitation,'' said state Sen. Dave Landis,
who has been in office since 1978. ''Voters ought to have a broad
of range of possibilities, the maximum number of qualified people
able to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska voters approved term limits for state senators and
members of Congress in 1992 and again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska Supreme Court threw out the first vote because too
few signatures had been collected to get the measure on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court invalidated the second vote, ruling that
states cannot limit federal terms.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Nebraska and nine other states tried ''scarlet
letter'' measures to identify those candidates who oppose
congressional term limits.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal appeals court said Nebraska's 1996 law to label
names on ballots that way would have ''the likely effect of
handicapping a class of candidates.'' Now such laws are under
review by the U.S. Supreme court, with a decision expected next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In states where term limits were enacted, some people are having
second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Gov. Angus King will have worked with four House speakers
and three Senate presidents by the time he reaches his two-term
limit. A former term limits supporter, King now believes Maine
voters made a mistake passing retroactive term limits for their
legislators in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ''The present system is too much of a revolving door,'' King, a
political independent, said recently. ''It's a complicated
business, and it takes time to learn the process.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't wash with Paul Jacob, director of Washington-based
U.S. Term Limits, which promotes term limits.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you have individuals who serve in office term after term
after term, those folks tend to lose touch and become removed from
life as an ordinary person,'' Jacob said. ''Politicians become
pretty dangerous when they learn the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Term Limits: http://www.termlimits.org
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska Legislature: http://www.unicam.state.ne.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
