<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Junta Stops Suu Kyi Leave  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) -- Pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi was
forced to turn back from a renewed attempt to assert her freedom of
movement Thursday, when she tried to board a train out of the
capital but authorities refused to issue her a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the 1991 Nobel
Peace Prize winner was later ''forcibly removed'' from the train
station, calling the actions by the military government an
''outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff at the train station followed an attempt by Suu Kui
and some of her supporters in August to travel by car out of the
capital of Yangon for political work only to be stopped on the road
and put under virtual house arrest until early this month.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Suu Kyi and several colleagues from her National
League for Democracy were allowed to go to the railway station but
were kept from boarding four consecutive trains for the 12-hour,
350-mile journey to Mandalay, the country's second-biggest city.
Suu Kyi and her party's leaders were told that all tickets to
Mandalay had been sold out, a party official said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, before Suu Kyi's arrival, security forces hauled scores
of Suu Kyi's supporters from the station.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi, deputy party leader Tin Oo and about 10 members of the
party's youth wing, sat in a waiting lounge after the last train to
Mandalay departed at 9:30 p.m. Plainclothes and uniformed police
were also in the waiting area, which was barred to ordinary
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi and the others waited for about four more hours inside
the station, then left in a convoy of cars. No marked police or
military or uniformed officers were seen in the convoy. Suu Kyi's
car was seen later at her residence.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if Suu Kyi and her backers were forced out of
the station, which was closed to journalists during the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Madeleine Albright said that Suu Kyi's
whereabouts were unknown after being ''forcibly removed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This blatant, heavy-handed action is only the latest outrage
committed against Aung San Suu Kyi and other party leaders by
Burmese authorities,'' she said in a statement. ''It is
unacceptible.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said in a statement that was ''appalled'' at the
government's treatment of Suu Kyi and the NLD, and called the
restraints on the party ''an affront to free peoples everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi won the Peace Prize for her struggle for democracy in
Myanmar, also known as Burma, which has been ruled by its military
since 1962. She was kept under house arrest from 1989 to 1995, and
her movements have remained heavily restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Although Suu Kyi's party won national elections in 1990 in a
landslide, the military government refused to honor the results.
</P>
<P>
   The junta disapproves of Suu Kyi's efforts to conduct party work
in the countryside and has physically prevented her from doing so
on several occasions -- the last time Aug. 24 when she tried to
drive to a southern town.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as security restrictions on Suu Kyi and her party were
lifted Sept. 14, she announced her intention to travel again and
dared the government to stop her.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi last tried to travel by train, also to Mandalay, in
March 1996, when authorities blocked her by saying her carriage had
developed mechanical problems and could not make the journey.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Oo, the party's second in command, said the same situation
could arise again, but said: ''If they stop the train we will go by
another train. And even if this is stopped we will wait until
another train is available.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Myanmar's Foreign Minister Win Aung told the
United Nations that his government has been under ''unfair
scrutiny'' and political pressure from other nations while it is
establishing its own kind of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The military has ruled Myanmar since 1962. The current generals
took power in 1988 after crushing a nationwide uprising for
democracy, killing thousands of people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
