<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS to INSERT AP bug  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A ''clean-cut'' law student and his brother are
facing criminal charges that they conspired to make $2 million by
selling secrets to lawyers representing tobacco companies in a
high-stakes lawsuit in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Wednesday in Manhattan federal court,
prosecutors revealed they were trying to negotiate a plea deal with
the Quinnipiac College student, Said Farraj, 27, and his brother,
Yeazid Farraj, 24, both of Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI arrested the pair in July on charges they stole
anti-tobacco lawyers' 400-page ''trial plan,'' and then tried to
peddle it through e-mail to defense attorneys for Philip Morris,
Inc. and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on the most serious charge - interstate theft -
they could be put behind bars for up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, Said Farraj's lawyer and a Philip Morris attorney
refused comment on Thursday. An attorney for Yeazid Farraj did not
return a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Said Farraj worked as a summer paralegal for a Manhattan law
firm, Orrick, Herrington &AMP; Sutcliffe, representing a trust which
has sued Philip Morris, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. and others,
alleging they contributed to asbestos-related illnesses, court
papers said. Damages in the civil case, expected to go to trial
later this year, could exceed $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Farraj ''was a bright guy, a very good worker, clean-cut,''
recalled attorney Michael Stopler.
</P>
<P>
   But Stopler said Farraj abruptly quit after only a month one
Friday in June. According to a statement by an FBI agent, tobacco
lawyers found an e-mail from someone with the screen name
''FlyGuy'' when they arrived at work the following Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The sender said he had obtained an electronic copy of the
plaintiffs' trial plan, and offered a sample of 80 pages. The
closely guarded plan spelled out strategy and contained depositions
and court exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we realized what it was, we immediately alerted the
plaintiffs,'' said one tobacco lawyer, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Stopler said his opponents ''did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   After the plaintiff lawyers contacted the FBI, an agent posing
as a defense lawyer sent an e-mail response saying he was
interesting in seeing the entire plan. ''FlyGuy'' said that would
cost $2 million, and proposed closing the deal at a McDonald's
restaurant in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Yeazid Farraj showed up at the McDonald's on July 21, where was
met by an undercover agent carrying a duffel bag with $200,000 and
wearing a concealed recording device, court papers said. When the
agent showed him the cash, Farraj allegedly assured him that the
entire trial plan would be e-mailed to tobacco lawyers by ''his
friend on Staten Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Once under arrest, Farraj told authorities that his brother had
hatched the plot after secretly downloading the trial plan, papers
said. The older brother was later arrested at their Staten Island
home; both men are free on $50,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   The case was first reported this week by The Smoking Gun
Website.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
