<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. U. Proposes Admission Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE LOCKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- University of California officials are
proposing a new road to admissions that could bring in more black
and Hispanic students, provided they take a detour through
community college.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which requires approval by faculty and regents,
would expand offers of guaranteed admission from the current top 4
percent of each high school to the top 12.5 percent at each high
school.
</P>
<P>
   The additional 8.5 percent would not get immediate entry to the
university system, but they would be simultaneously admitted to a
university and to a community college and told what courses they
need to complete the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Because students would transfer as upperclassmen, the new
program doesn't take away freshman seats. University officials say
they have the capacity to handle up to 3,500 new transfers expected
from the new program by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The approach could boost enrollment of black, Hispanic and
American Indian students, whose numbers have fallen since the
university system scuttled affirmative action five years ago. The
program could make up to 12,700 more students eligible for
admission. Of those, up to 36 percent are Hispanic, black or
American Indian, the three groups considered underrepresented in
the university system. By contrast, underrepresented minorities
make up 12 percent of the current pool of eligible freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, it will have an impact on the number of
underrepresented minorities,'' system President Richard C. Atkinson
said at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new program won't violate Proposition 209, which
forbids affirmative action in public education because it doesn't
select by race.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California now accepts the top 12.5 percent of
all high school students, which means high-performing schools send
lots of students to university campuses while low-performing
schools send few or none.
</P>
<P>
   If the new program is approved by faculty and regents, students
will be identified at the beginning of their senior year on the
basis of student transcripts and invited to apply to the program.
</P>
<P>
   But Regent Ward Connerly, who led the fight to ban affirmative
action at the university and statewide through voter-approved
Proposition 209, said he'd need some assurance academic quality
won't slip under the proposed change.
</P>
<P>
   He also wishes officials weren't running demographic breakdowns
of the potential new students.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the intent is to somehow influence the number of
underrepresented minorities, then I think that's breaking the
law,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 2237 </TRAILER>
