<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones and Greene Set Out To Win  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- They are the fastest woman and the
fastest man in the world. Last time around, they both missed out.
This time, they are determined not to.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones and Maurice Greene both make their bids for gold on
Saturday, in their first Olympics. Barring injury or a miraculous
failure to qualify, all eyes will be on them for the 100-meter
dash, the ultimate sprint and traditionally the most-watched event
in track.
</P>
<P>
   For both athletes, there was heartbreak four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has captivated fans with her charisma, poise, smarts
and above all talent, missed out on the Atlanta Games when she
broke a bone in her foot playing basketball in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The famous story goes that Jones, at age 8, watched the Olympics
come to Los Angeles. She erased some homework assignments on a
chalkboard and instead wrote: ''I want to be an Olympic champion.''
</P>
<P>
   That determination has never wavered. Only now, at 24, she would
more precisely add: ''I want to be an Olympic champion five
times.'' Because she is on a quest for five gold medals at these
games.
</P>
<P>
   No female track athlete has done that in one Olympics -- in fact,
not even in an entire career. But Jones is so serenely confident
that she makes people believe she can.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just show up and give me a race,'' she has said.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence was on display Friday as Jones smiled broadly
for the crowd, then breezed to victory in her 100-meter opening
heat in 11.20.
</P>
<P>
   She was a basketball star at North Carolina, then turned her
attention fully to track. In the summer of 1997, she won the 100
meters at the world championships. In 1998, she was the World Cup
champion in the 100, 200 and long jump. She competed in 36 outdoor
events in 1998, and won 35 of them. In 1999, she repeated as 100
world champion and placed third in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   She idolizes Olympic star Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who she says has
told her about ''the Olympic spirit that everybody talks about.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She says it's unlike anything you've ever experienced,'' Jones
says. ''That's what I want to experience. That's what I want to
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene wants to feel it, too. Maybe that's why his license plate
reads: ''MO GOLD.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Jones, Greene lost out on the experience four years ago. He
failed to make the U.S. team, and drove to Atlanta, where he cried
uncontrollably as he watched the 100-meter dash from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   He recovered to win two world championships, and to set a world
record of 9.79.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the man who calls himself ''the phenomenon'' exudes
confidence about his chances at Sydney, where he made a good start
Friday by easily winning his first qualifying heat in 10.31.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is coming after me now,'' he said last year. ''Fine,
let them keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think about Sydney, and I can't wait. I just can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the top-billed track races, NBC will say goodbye
to swimming, on a day when American Amy van Dyken is set to defend
her Olympic title in the 50-freestyle. But she faces the red-hot
Inge de Bruijn. The Dutchwoman already has won two gold medals in
these games, and she owns the world record in the 50 free. Also
racing is Australian star Susie O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   The vigorous U.S.-Australia rivalry could bring an exciting
finish to swimming at the Aquatic Center, with both men and women
competing in the 400 medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's primetime coverage also features women's mountain-bike
cycling and men's platform diving.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be forgotten is baseball, where an unheralded U.S. team,
staffed mostly by minor-leaguers, has surprised many with its
success. They face powerhouse Cuba on Saturday, in a game to be
featured by MSNBC during the day.
</P>
<P>
   The once-invincible Cubans were stunned by the Netherlands
earlier in the week, ending their Olympic winning streak at 21
games.
</P>
<P>
   Also on MSNBC is men's soccer and the women's gold-medal match
in water polo. CNBC has men's water polo, boxing and sailing.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will also have late-night coverage of men's volleyball and
weightlifting, and daytime coverage of basketball, rowing, beach
volleyball and the men's trampoline final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-21-00 2250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
