<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-21 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies 6, Mets 5  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Omar Daal didn't disappoint Brian Kingman,
even though he had nothing to show for a strong outing.
</P>
<P>
   Daal allowed one run over six innings as he avoided becoming the
first 20-game loser in 20 years, and Pat Burrell drove in the
winning run with a bases-loaded single in the ninth as the
Philadelphia Phillies beat the New York Mets 6-5 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Lee hit his first homer as a Phillie and Bobby Abreu also
homered as Philadelphia wasted a 5-1 lead, then recovered to defeat
the Mets for the seventh time in 10 games this season. New York
dropped to 7-13 in September.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets scored tied it in the ninth against Jeff Brantley
(2-7) on a home run by Todd Zeile and a pinch RBI double by Robin
Ventura, the Phillies rallied off Rick White (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   Doug Glanville led off the ninth with a single, took third on
Abreu's double off the left-field wall and scored on Burrell's
single after an intentional walk to Scott Rolen. Burrell is
8-for-11 with 20 RBIs when batting with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Daal, acquired along with Lee and two others July 26 from
Arizona for Curt Schilling, allowed one run and six hits and left
with a 5-1 lead. He remained 3-19 and is 0-7 in eight starts since
beating San Diego on Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Daal, a 16-game winner last year, failed to become to become the
first 20-game loser since Kingman for Oakland in 1980. Kingman flew
in from California to watch the game at Veterans Stadium, and was
thrilled with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be the last 20-game loser,'' said Kingman, who
called a reporter for directions to the stadium after his flight
landed in Baltimore. ''I suffered so much doing it. Now, it's kind
of fun so I want to get some mileage out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingman plans to go to Chicago for Daal's next start, scheduled
for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York dropped 4&AMP;frac12; games behind first-place Atlanta in the NL
East. The Mets, who have lost seven of their last eight games at
Veterans Stadium, began the night five games ahead of Los Angeles
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed allowed five runs -- four earned -- and eight hits in 5
1-3 innings -- his shortest outing since July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Prince hit an RBI grounder in the second, Abreu homered in
the third and Lee connected in the fourth -- his first home run in
154 at-bats since July 4 for Arizona against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Payton homered in the fifth, but the Phillies scored twice
in the sixth on Reed's wild pickoff attempt with a runner on third
and Prince's RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gomes let the Mets back into the game by walking the bases
loaded in the seventh. Vicente Padilla walked Benny Agbayani,
forcing in a run, and pinch-hitter Mike Piazza singled in a run --
making him 10-for-53 (.189) in September with five RBIs. With the
bases loaded and two outs, Padilla struck out Todd Pratt.
</P>
<P>
Notes@: The Phillies have won 10 of the last 13 against the Mets
dating to last season. ... Piazza and Ventura didn't start. Ventura
is hitting .219 in September (14-for-64). ... Abreu is 10-for-21
(.476) against Reed. ... Rolen was 1-for-16 against Reed before
hitting a single in the first. ... Daal was 2-10 with a 7.22 ERA in
Arizona. He's 1-9 with a 4.85 ERA with the Phillies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
