<HEADLINE> Australia 7, Russia 6 in Water Polo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The hometown crowd got a scare, but
Bridgette Gusterson sent them into hysterics and Australia into the
gold-medal game.
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies rallied from two goals down to defeat Russia 7-6
Friday (Thursday night EDT) and move into the finals of the first
women's Olympic water polo tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gusterson, the team captain, backhanded the ball past Russia's
Marina Akobia with 43.4 seconds to go. But until then, it looked
like Saturday night's gold-medal match with either the United
States or Netherlands would be a much quieter affair.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians were up 6-4 on Irina Tolkounova's goal right before
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Watson, a 35-year-old who came out of retirement for the
Olympics, began the rally. She broke up the Russian attack that
brought the tying goal, a long center shot with 1:32 remaining that
sent the 4,000 at Ryde Aquatic Leisure Center screaming.
</P>
<P>
   Sofia Konoukh tried to dump a pass low, but it was taken by
Aussie goalie Liz Weekes.
</P>
<P>
   Gusterson found herself free on the next possession and, with
her back to the net, rifled the ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
   That ensured a packed house for the gold-medal game, played at
the 17,500-seat Sydney International Aquatic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bronwyn Mayer had three goals for Australia, who have lost only
one of its six games here.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will meet the Netherlands on Friday night in
the other semifinal.
</P>
</TEXT>
